{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_nayathjv684y_2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: How The Enneagram System Works - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/how-the-enneagram-system-works/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\npoint of view,\n[...]\nEnneagram can be seen as a set of nine distinct personality types, with each number on the Enneagram denoting one type. It is common to find a little of yourself in all nine of the types, although one of\n[...]\nshould stand out as being closest to yourself. This is your\n[...]\nAs we have seen with the Levels of Development, the\n[...]\npersonality types of the Enneagram are not static categories: they reflect our change over time. Further, the sequence of\n[...]\ntypes and the arrangement of the inner lines of the symbol are not arbitrary. The inner lines of the Enneagram connect the types in a sequence that denotes what each type will do under different conditions. There are two lines connected to each type, and they connect with two other types. One line connects with a type that represents how a person of the first type behaves when they are moving toward health and growth. This is called the Direction of Integration or Growth. The other line goes to another type that represents how the person is likely to act out if they are under increased stress and pressure—when they feel they are not in control of the situation. This second line is called the Direction of Stress or Disintegration. In other words, different situations will evoke different kinds of responses from your personality. You will respond or adapt in different directions, as indicated by the lines of the Enneagram from your basic type. Again, we see the flexibility and dynamism of the Enneagram.\n[...]\nThe Direction of Integration\n[...]\nindicated for each\n[...]\nby the reverse of the\n[...]\ndisintegration. Each type moves toward integration in a direction that is the opposite of its unhealthy direction. Thus, the\n[...]\nfor the Direction of Integration is 1-7-\n[...]\n-1: an integrating One goes to Seven, an\n[...]\n, an integrating Eight goes to Two, an integrating Two goes to Four, and an\n[...]\n. On the equilateral triangle, the\n[...]\nwill go to\n[...]\nwill go to\n[...]\n, and an integrating\n[...]\nwill go to Nine. You can see how this works by following\n[...]\ndirection of the arrows on the following Enneagram.\n[...]\nthe types in both your Direction of Integration or Growth and your Direction of Disintegration or Stress are important influences. To obtain a complete\n[...]\n(or of someone\n[...]\n), you must take into consideration the basic type\n[...]\nthe two types in\n[...]\nof Integration and Disintegration. The factors represented by those four types blend into your total personality and provide the framework for understanding the\n[...]\noperating in you. For example, no one is\n[...]\nA Two has either a One-\n[...]\n, and the Two’s Direction of Dis\n[...]\n) and its Direction of Integration (Four) also play important parts in\n\n---\n\nTitle: Stress and Growth Lines\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/lines/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe lines inside the Enneagram symbol — the equilateral triangle on points 3, 6, and 9 and the irregular hexagon on points 1, 4, 2, 8, 5, and 7 — are not decoration. Each type sits at a vertex with exactly two lines extending from it, connecting to two other non-adjacent types. These connections are called the type's stress and growth points (sometimes disintegration and integration points), and they describe predictable directions in which each type tends to move under pressure or in conditions that support development.\n[...]\nThe inner triangle connects points 3, 6, and 9 to each other. These three are the representative types of the three centers of intelligence — Type 9 anchors the Body center, Type 3 anchors the Heart center, Type 6 anchors the Head center. They form a closed loop: 9 → 3 → 6 → 9.\n[...]\nThe standard framing, established by Don Riso and Russ Hudson and widely adopted across the Enneagram tradition, is:\n[...]\nDirection of stress (disintegration): 1 → 4 → 2 → 8 → 5 → 7 → 1, and 9 → 6 → 3 → 9.\n[...]\nDirection of growth (integration): 1 → 7 → 5 → 8 → 2 → 4 → 1, and 9 → 3 → 6 → 9.\n[...]\nThe growth sequence is exactly the stress sequence reversed. Each type's growth direction is the type whose stress direction points to it. Type 1 grows toward Type 7, and Type 7 stresses toward Type 1. Type 5 grows toward Type 8, and Type 8 stresses toward Type 5. The full set:\n[...]\nThe standard Riso/Hudson framing is that movement along the lines is not constant but correlates with the type's level of development. The Levels of Development — Riso and Hudson's nine-level scale describing the continuum from a type's healthiest to most constricted expression — interact with the lines in a specific way.\n[...]\n, a person tends to take on the\n[...]\n. A Type\n[...]\n; a Type\n[...]\n. The stress direction does not\n[...]\nAt healthy levels, a person tends to access the patterns of their growth direction in their higher-functioning form. A Type 1 at healthy levels accesses the spontaneity and joy of a healthy Seven; a Type 1 at the highest levels accesses the deepest gifts of integrated Seven. The growth direction is not accessed by deciding to access it; it tends to come online as a person's general level of functioning rises.\n[...]\n— how the core\n[...]\nexpresses itself across most situations. A 5\n[...]\nfrom a\n[...]\nw6 in everyday\n[...]\n. (T\n[...]\nat the wings page\n[...]\nLines describe directional movement — patterns the core type takes on under specific conditions (stress) or as a function of integration (growth). A Type 5 doesn't always look like a Type 7 or a Type 8; they take on those patterns under particular conditions. Lines are about dynamic shifts.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Discovering Your Personality Type\nURL: https://cdn.bookey.app/files/pdf/book/en/discovering-your-personality-type.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Don Richard Riso\nHighlights:\nof the human psyche with the revised\n[...]\nedition of \"Discovering Your Personality Type\" by Don\n[...]\nRichard Riso and Russ Hudson, the foremost authorities on the\n[...]\nEnneagram. This essential guide introduces readers to the nine\n[...]\ndistinct personality types, providing a foundational\n[...]\nunderstanding of how to identify their own characteristics\n[...]\nthrough the scientifically validated Riso-Hudson Enneagram\n[...]\nType Indicator (RHETI). Simplified for beginners, this\n[...]\nupdated edition not only presents a practical framework for\n[...]\npersonal growth but also offers valuable insights applicable in\n[...]\nvarious areas of life, such as professional development,\n[...]\n. With its accurate and\n[...]\nWhat Is the Enneagram? A geometric figure categorizing nine personality types, it reveals communication styles\n[...]\n(RHETI)\n[...]\nWhat Is the Enneagram?\n \nThe Enneagram is a geometric figure that categorizes nine\nbasic personality types and their interactions. Each type\npossesses distinct communication styles and values,\nenriching our understanding of human behavior. Rather than\nconfining individuals, it reveals their current state and\npotential pathways for growth.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram consists of a circle with nine equidistant\npoints, each representing a distinct personality type from one\nto nine. Inner lines connect various points, with points Three,\nSix, and Nine forming an equilateral triangle, while the\nremaining points create an irregular hexagram. These\nconnections have significant meanings in understanding\npersonality dynamics.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram identifies nine core personality types, with\n[...]\nThe Triads\n[...]\nThe nine types are categorized into three Triads—Instinctive,\nFeeling, and Thinking—each sharing common emotional\nthemes: anger, shame, and anxiety, respectively. Each type in\nthe Triad copes differently with their dominant emotion,\nleading to a variety of characteristics and behaviors.\n[...]\nEach personality type is influenced by adjacent types, known\nas wings. These wings enhance or contrast with the primary\ntype, adding complexity to each person's personality.\n[...]\nThe Levels of Development\n[...]\nPersonality types have internal structures defined by nine\n[...]\nLevels of Development. These Levels illustrate how people\ncan change over time, displaying healthy, average, or\nunhealthy traits, thus offering insights for personal growth\nand therapy.\n[...]\nDirections of Integration and Disintegration\n[...]\nEach type has specific behavioral patterns in stress\n(Disintegration) and security (Integration), denoted by\nconnections between types. Understanding these patterns\nallows for deeper personal insight and offers pathways for\ndevelopment.\n\n---\n\nTitle: N/A\nURL: https://ia600405.us.archive.org/27/items/TheWisdomOfTheEnneagram.TheCompleteGuideToPsychologicalAndSpiritualGrowthForTheN/The%20Wisdom%20of%20the%20Enneagram.%20The%20Complete%20Guide%20to%20Psychological%20and%20Spiritual%20Growth%20for%20the%20Nine%20Personality%20Types%20by%20Don%20Richard%20Riso%20and%20Russ%20Hudson.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nNine Personality Types\n[...]\nDON RICHARD RISO and RUSS HUDSON\n[...]\nLntroducing the NineTypes 10\n[...]\n5 The Triadic Self 49\n[...]\nThe Triads 49\n[...]\n6 Dynamics and Variations 69\n[...]\nThe Wings 69\n[...]\n70\n[...]\nThe Levels ofDevelopment 75\n[...]\nThe Directions ofIntegration\n[...]\nandDisintegration 87\n[...]\nII T THE NINE PERSONALITY TYPES 95\n[...]\n7 Type One: THE REFORMER 97\n[...]\n8 Type Two: THE HELPER 125\n[...]\n9 Type Three: THE ACHIEVER 151\n[...]\n10 Type Four: THE INDIVIDUALIST 178\n[...]\n11 Type Five: THE INVESTIGATOR 206\n[...]\n13 Type Seven: THE ENTHUSIAST 260\n[...]\n14 Type Eight: THE CHALLENGER 287\n[...]\n15 Type Nine: THE PEACEMAKER 314\n[...]\nTHE ENNEAGRAM (pronounced \"ANY-a-gram\") isa geometric figure\n[...]\nthat maps out the nine fundamental personality types of human nature\n[...]\nand their complex interrelationships. It is a development of modern\n[...]\npsychology that has roots in spiritual wisdom from many different an\n[...]\ncient traditions.- The word Enneagram comes from the Greek for\n[...]\n\"nine\"—ennea—and \"figure\"—grammos; thus, it isa \"nine-pointed fig\u0002ure.\n[...]\nINTRODUCING THE NINE TYPES\n[...]\nWhile we will recognize in ourselves behaviors of all nine types,\n[...]\nour most defining characteristics are rooted in one of these types. On\n[...]\npage 13 you will find a questionnaire, the Riso-Hudson QUEST, that\n[...]\ncan help you narrow down your basic type, and at the beginning of\n[...]\neach type chapter there is a second independent test, the Riso-Hudson\n[...]\nTAS or Type Attitude Sorter, to help you check your findings.\n[...]\nType One: TheReformer. The principled, idealistic type. Ones are\n[...]\nType Two: The Helper. The caring, interpersonal type. Twos are\n[...]\nType Three: The Achiever. The adaptable, success-oriented type.\n[...]\nType Four: The Individualist. The romantic, introspective type.\n[...]\nType Five: The Investigator. The intense, cerebral\n[...]\nType Six: The Loyalist. The committed, security-oriented type.\n[...]\nType Seven: The Enthusiast. The busy, productive type. Sevens are\n[...]\nType Eight: The Challenger. The powerful, dominating type.\n[...]\nType Nine: The Peacemaker. The easygoing, self-effacing type.\n[...]\nbut can also be too willing to go\n[...]\nThe first questionnaire, which follows on pages 14-15, is the Riso\u0002Hudson QUEST, the\n[...]\nThe secondset of questionnaires is the Riso-Hudson TAS,\n[...]\nA major breakthrough camein 1977when he discovered the Levels\n[...]\nof Development. The Levels revealed the gradations of growth and de\n[...]\nterioration that people actually move through in their lives. They\n[...]\nshowed which traits and motivations wentwith which types, and why.\n[...]\nMost profoundly, they indicated the degrees of our identification with\n[...]\nHe also empha\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Centers of Intelligence: Head, Heart, Gut\nURL: https://enneagramuserguide.com/enneagram-guide/enneagram-centers\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram centers, sometimes referred to as \" the triads,\" define three types of intelligence we use to process or relate to the world: the head, the heart, and the gut. Each of the nine Enneagram personality types is preoccupied more with one center than the other two.\n[...]\nThe three centers of intelligence for the Enneagram types are commonly called the head or head-based center, the heart of heart-based center, and the gut or body-based center.\n[...]\nThe types pointed to by the triangle on the Enneagram symbol (3, 6, and 9) lie in the middle of each center. The types on either side of 3, 6, and 9 make up the two other types in those centers.\n[...]\n- 567: Head or Head-Based Types\n- 234: Heart or Heart-Based Types\n- 891: Gut or Body-Based Types\n[...]\ndeficiency for not living up to a\n[...]\nidealized sense of self.\n[...]\nThe anger triad consists of types 8, 9, and 1. Anger for these types involves the gut or body center. It can be thought of as an energy of will that pushes against obstacles to create movement or resists being pushed.\n[...]\nThe Enne\n[...]\ntypes evolved from\n[...]\nIchazo's ego-types which represented nine types of\n[...]\nfixation. Although an individual would identify a single fixation to work on, a more complete approach was to identify one fixation from each of the three centers. This was called a person's tri-fix.\n[...]\nany trademark or copyright issues\n[...]\nthe tri-center approach.\n[...]\nWith the tri-center approach, as applied to the Enneagram personality types, an individual identifies a dominant gut type, heart type, and head type. There can also be an order of preference for those three dominant types or centers as well.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram personality types group the nine types into three centers of intelligence often referred to as the gut, heart, and head centers.\n[...]\nDominant Type in Each Center with Wings Test This test determines your dominant type in each center (aka tri-center, trifix, tritype, truetype) along with the wings of those types.Use when you want to know your tri-center or tri-center with wings.\n[...]\n- Enneagram Type Preference Test This test produces a scored list of all nine types.Questions are forced-choice, similar to the method used by the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indictor (RHETI).Use to determine type, wings, gut/heart/head types, and tri-center.\n- Center Type Comparison Test This test scores the three types in a given center to determine your dominant type within that center (gut, heart, or head type).Use when you don't know your dominant type for one of the centers.\n[...]\n- primary type\n- candidate types\n- preferred wing\n- intinctual subtype\n- instinctual variant stacking\n- center types (gut, heart, and head)\n- tri-center with wings\n\n---\n\nTitle: Levels of Development - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/levels-of-development/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThere is an internal structure within each personality type. That structure is the continuum of behaviors, attitudes, defenses, and motivations formed by the nine Levels of Development which make up the personality type itself. This discovery (and the working out of all the traits that comprise each type) was originally made by Don Riso in 1977, and was further developed by Don with Russ Hudson in the 1990s. They are the only Enneagram teachers to include this important factor in their treatment of the Enneagram. The Levels are an important contribution not only to the Enneagram but to ego psychology — and the personality types of the Enneagram cannot be adequately explained without them. The Levels account for differences among people of the same type as well as how people change for better or for worse. The Levels can also help therapists and counselors pinpoint what is actually going on with clients and suggest solutions to the problems they may be confronting.\n[...]\nby understanding the\n[...]\n, one can see\n[...]\n—and how\n[...]\nnoted, without the Levels, the Enneagram is\n[...]\nThe continuum is comprised of nine internal Levels of Development—briefly, there are three Levels in the healthy section, three Levels in the average section, and three Levels in the unhealthy section. It may help you to think of the continuum of Levels as a photographer’s gray scale which has gradations from pure white to pure black with many shades of gray in between. On the continuum, the healthiest traits appear first, at the top, so to speak. As we move down the continuum in a spiral pattern, we progressively pass through each Level of Development marking a distinct shift in the personality’s deterioration to the pure black of psychological breakdown at the bottom. The continuum for each of the personality types can be seen in the following diagram.\n[...]\n- Level 4: The Level of Imbalance/ Social Role\n- Level 5: The Level of Interpersonal Control\n- Level 6: The Level of Overcompensation\n[...]\n- Level 7: The Level of Violation\n- Level 8: The Level of Obsession and Compulsion\n- Level 9: The Level of Pathological Destructiveness\n[...]\nBy contrast, the movement\n[...]\nhealth, up the Levels, is simultaneous with being more present and awake in our minds, hearts, and bodies. As we become more present, we become less fixated in\n[...]\ndefensive structures of our personality and are more attuned and open to ourselves and our environment. We see our personality objectively in action rather than “falling asleep” to our\n[...]\n“not doing” our personality and of gaining some real distance from\n\n---\n\nTitle: Levels of Development\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/levels/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe framework that names this difference is the Levels of Development, a nine-level scale developed by Don Riso in 1977 and refined with Russ Hudson through the 1990s. The framework describes how each Enneagram type expresses itself across a range from psychological liberation at the top to pathological constriction at the bottom. Same type, nine different qualities of expression.\n[...]\nThis page covers the structure of the\n[...]\n, the three\n[...]\n, what each\n[...]\ninteract with the other Enneagram elements (\n[...]\n, lines, subtypes\n[...]\nof working with levels in self-observation.\n[...]\nThe Levels of Development are nine levels, grouped into three bands of three levels each:\n[...]\n- Healthy: Levels 1, 2, 3\n- Average: Levels 4, 5, 6\n- Unhealthy: Levels 7, 8, 9\n[...]\nruns from highest functioning\n[...]\nmost constricted (Level 9\n[...]\nhas a structural-function name — describing what the ego is doing at that level, what defense mechanism is operating, what relationship to one\n[...]\n| Level | Name | Band | |---|---|---| | 1 | The Level of Liberation | Healthy | | 2 | The Level of Psychological Capacity | Healthy | | 3 | The Level of Social Value | Healthy | | 4 | The Level of Imbalance / Social Role | Average | | 5 | The Level of Interpersonal Control | Average | | 6 | The Level of Overcompensation | Average | | 7 | The Level of Violation | Unhealthy | | 8 | The Level of Obsession and Compulsion | Unhealthy | | 9 | The Level of Pathological Destructiveness | Unhealthy |\n[...]\nThis is the most concrete interaction. The Riso-Hudson framing is that stress-direction movement (along the disintegration line) tends to be activated at average-to-unhealthy levels, while growth-direction movement (along the integration line) tends to be accessed at healthy levels. A Type 1 at average levels begins exhibiting average-to-unhealthy Type 4 patterns under sustained pressure (moodiness, brooding, self-absorption). A Type 1 at healthy levels accesses healthy Type 7 patterns spontaneously (lightness, openness, spontaneity).\n[...]\nThe contribution of the wing also shifts by level. At healthy levels, a person can access the gifts of their wing as additional resource. At average levels, the wing's coloration is most visible — this is where 5w4s look distinctively different from 5w6s. At unhealthy levels, the wing's constrictions compound the type's, sometimes producing the most difficult-to-distinguish presentations.\n[...]\nWings describe steady-state coloration: how the core type expresses itself flavored by the adjacent type. Wings are about ongoing presentation.\n[...]\nLevels describe vertical functioning: how integrated or constricted the type expression is at a given time. Levels are about quality of expression.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Triads: Centers (Mind, Heart, Gut) and Others - Personality Science\nURL: https://enneagramtest.net/personality/enneagram/triads/\nPublished: 2023-07-01T18:15:44.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram contains many kinds of triads, which is a group of three. The main triads of the Enneagram are based on the three centers of intelligence: mind, heart, and gut (or body), which give rise to the thinking, feeling, and instinctive triads.\n[...]\nAll 9 Enneagram types are divided into three triads based on these centers, and each type reflects the emotions and issues of its respective center in a unique way. Those triads are:\n[...]\n- Mind: Types 5, 6, 7\n- Heart: Types 2, 3, 4\n- Body/Gut: Types 8, 9, 1\n[...]\n. This results in a fear about the future and not having\n[...]\nneeds to be\n[...]\n. The three\n[...]\nof the heart triad are\n[...]\nGut Center: Instinct\n[...]\nThe gut or body center is responsible for instinct, and particularly for planning for the future. This results in a preoccupation with boundaries, and anger from boundaries being transgressed or violated. The three types of the gut triad are 8, 9, and 1, and each type experiences the gut center differently and deals with its issues in a particular way:\n[...]\n6, 7\n[...]\nHeart | 2, 3, 4\n[...]\n| Shame | Image |\n[...]\n| Gut / Body | 8, 9, 1 | Instinctive | Anger | Autonomy |\n[...]\nThe Object Relations triads are based on three particular object relations, which Don Riso called “Dominant Affects”:\n[...]\n- Attachment (Type 3, 6, 9): The “positive” object relation that one feels in relationship with another person when one’s needs are being met. This was called the “central” object relation by object relations theorists.\n- Rejection (Types 2, 5, 8): The object relation that results from one’s emotional needs being disregarded or rejected.\n- Frustration (Types 1, 4, 7): The object relation that results from one’s emotional needs being inconsistently or unreliably met.\n[...]\n1, 2,\n[...]\n(inner critics). Compliant types are sometimes called Dutiful\n[...]\n. The superego represent the internalized\n[...]\n- Assertive\n[...]\nTypes 3, 7, 8.\n[...]\n: Types 4, 5, 9.\n[...]\n| Enneagram Type | Center | Relation to Center | Object Relations | Harmonics | Hornevian Group |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Type 1 | Gut | Under-express | Frustration | Competency | Compliant |\n| Type 2 | Heart | Over-express | Rejection | Positive Outlook | Compliant |\n| Type 3 | Heart | Repress | Attachment | Competency | Assertive |\n| Type 4 | Heart | Under-express | Frustration | Reactive | Withdrawn |\n| Type 5 | Mind | Over-express | Rejection | Competency | Withdrawn |\n| Type 6 | Mind | Repress | Attachment | Reactive | Compliant |\n| Type 7 | Mind | Under-express | Frustration | Positive Outlook | Assertive |\n| Type 8 | Gut | Over-express | Rejection | Reactive | Assertive |\n| Type 9 | Gut | Repress | Attachment | Positive Outlook | Withdrawn |"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a88ea885-1950-40b9-b15d-36f548aa1b64","uuid":"20b97552-6a7e-43ae-9b4a-ecdf7986fb7e","timestamp":"2026-06-10T16:54:18.226Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: How The Enneagram System Works - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/how-the-enneagram-system-works/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\npoint of view,\n[...]\nEnneagram can be seen as a set of nine distinct personality types, with each number on the Enneagram denoting one type. It is common to find a little of yourself in all nine of the types, although one of\n[...]\nshould stand out as being closest to yourself. This is your\n[...]\nAs we have seen with the Levels of Development, the\n[...]\npersonality types of the Enneagram are not static categories: they reflect our change over time. Further, the sequence of\n[...]\ntypes and the arrangement of the inner lines of the symbol are not arbitrary. The inner lines of the Enneagram connect the types in a sequence that denotes what each type will do under different conditions. There are two lines connected to each type, and they connect with two other types. One line connects with a type that represents how a person of the first type behaves when they are moving toward health and growth. This is called the Direction of Integration or Growth. The other line goes to another type that represents how the person is likely to act out if they are under increased stress and pressure—when they feel they are not in control of the situation. This second line is called the Direction of Stress or Disintegration. In other words, different situations will evoke different kinds of responses from your personality. You will respond or adapt in different directions, as indicated by the lines of the Enneagram from your basic type. Again, we see the flexibility and dynamism of the Enneagram.\n[...]\nThe Direction of Integration\n[...]\nindicated for each\n[...]\nby the reverse of the\n[...]\ndisintegration. Each type moves toward integration in a direction that is the opposite of its unhealthy direction. Thus, the\n[...]\nfor the Direction of Integration is 1-7-\n[...]\n-1: an integrating One goes to Seven, an\n[...]\n, an integrating Eight goes to Two, an integrating Two goes to Four, and an\n[...]\n. On the equilateral triangle, the\n[...]\nwill go to\n[...]\nwill go to\n[...]\n, and an integrating\n[...]\nwill go to Nine. You can see how this works by following\n[...]\ndirection of the arrows on the following Enneagram.\n[...]\nthe types in both your Direction of Integration or Growth and your Direction of Disintegration or Stress are important influences. To obtain a complete\n[...]\n(or of someone\n[...]\n), you must take into consideration the basic type\n[...]\nthe two types in\n[...]\nof Integration and Disintegration. The factors represented by those four types blend into your total personality and provide the framework for understanding the\n[...]\noperating in you. For example, no one is\n[...]\nA Two has either a One-\n[...]\n, and the Two’s Direction of Dis\n[...]\n) and its Direction of Integration (Four) also play important parts in\n\n---\n\nTitle: Stress and Growth Lines\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/lines/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe lines inside the Enneagram symbol — the equilateral triangle on points 3, 6, and 9 and the irregular hexagon on points 1, 4, 2, 8, 5, and 7 — are not decoration. Each type sits at a vertex with exactly two lines extending from it, connecting to two other non-adjacent types. These connections are called the type's stress and growth points (sometimes disintegration and integration points), and they describe predictable directions in which each type tends to move under pressure or in conditions that support development.\n[...]\nThe inner triangle connects points 3, 6, and 9 to each other. These three are the representative types of the three centers of intelligence — Type 9 anchors the Body center, Type 3 anchors the Heart center, Type 6 anchors the Head center. They form a closed loop: 9 → 3 → 6 → 9.\n[...]\nThe standard framing, established by Don Riso and Russ Hudson and widely adopted across the Enneagram tradition, is:\n[...]\nDirection of stress (disintegration): 1 → 4 → 2 → 8 → 5 → 7 → 1, and 9 → 6 → 3 → 9.\n[...]\nDirection of growth (integration): 1 → 7 → 5 → 8 → 2 → 4 → 1, and 9 → 3 → 6 → 9.\n[...]\nThe growth sequence is exactly the stress sequence reversed. Each type's growth direction is the type whose stress direction points to it. Type 1 grows toward Type 7, and Type 7 stresses toward Type 1. Type 5 grows toward Type 8, and Type 8 stresses toward Type 5. The full set:\n[...]\nThe standard Riso/Hudson framing is that movement along the lines is not constant but correlates with the type's level of development. The Levels of Development — Riso and Hudson's nine-level scale describing the continuum from a type's healthiest to most constricted expression — interact with the lines in a specific way.\n[...]\n, a person tends to take on the\n[...]\n. A Type\n[...]\n; a Type\n[...]\n. The stress direction does not\n[...]\nAt healthy levels, a person tends to access the patterns of their growth direction in their higher-functioning form. A Type 1 at healthy levels accesses the spontaneity and joy of a healthy Seven; a Type 1 at the highest levels accesses the deepest gifts of integrated Seven. The growth direction is not accessed by deciding to access it; it tends to come online as a person's general level of functioning rises.\n[...]\n— how the core\n[...]\nexpresses itself across most situations. A 5\n[...]\nfrom a\n[...]\nw6 in everyday\n[...]\n. (T\n[...]\nat the wings page\n[...]\nLines describe directional movement — patterns the core type takes on under specific conditions (stress) or as a function of integration (growth). A Type 5 doesn't always look like a Type 7 or a Type 8; they take on those patterns under particular conditions. Lines are about dynamic shifts.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Discovering Your Personality Type\nURL: https://cdn.bookey.app/files/pdf/book/en/discovering-your-personality-type.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Don Richard Riso\nHighlights:\nof the human psyche with the revised\n[...]\nedition of \"Discovering Your Personality Type\" by Don\n[...]\nRichard Riso and Russ Hudson, the foremost authorities on the\n[...]\nEnneagram. This essential guide introduces readers to the nine\n[...]\ndistinct personality types, providing a foundational\n[...]\nunderstanding of how to identify their own characteristics\n[...]\nthrough the scientifically validated Riso-Hudson Enneagram\n[...]\nType Indicator (RHETI). Simplified for beginners, this\n[...]\nupdated edition not only presents a practical framework for\n[...]\npersonal growth but also offers valuable insights applicable in\n[...]\nvarious areas of life, such as professional development,\n[...]\n. With its accurate and\n[...]\nWhat Is the Enneagram? A geometric figure categorizing nine personality types, it reveals communication styles\n[...]\n(RHETI)\n[...]\nWhat Is the Enneagram?\n \nThe Enneagram is a geometric figure that categorizes nine\nbasic personality types and their interactions. Each type\npossesses distinct communication styles and values,\nenriching our understanding of human behavior. Rather than\nconfining individuals, it reveals their current state and\npotential pathways for growth.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram consists of a circle with nine equidistant\npoints, each representing a distinct personality type from one\nto nine. Inner lines connect various points, with points Three,\nSix, and Nine forming an equilateral triangle, while the\nremaining points create an irregular hexagram. These\nconnections have significant meanings in understanding\npersonality dynamics.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram identifies nine core personality types, with\n[...]\nThe Triads\n[...]\nThe nine types are categorized into three Triads—Instinctive,\nFeeling, and Thinking—each sharing common emotional\nthemes: anger, shame, and anxiety, respectively. Each type in\nthe Triad copes differently with their dominant emotion,\nleading to a variety of characteristics and behaviors.\n[...]\nEach personality type is influenced by adjacent types, known\nas wings. These wings enhance or contrast with the primary\ntype, adding complexity to each person's personality.\n[...]\nThe Levels of Development\n[...]\nPersonality types have internal structures defined by nine\n[...]\nLevels of Development. These Levels illustrate how people\ncan change over time, displaying healthy, average, or\nunhealthy traits, thus offering insights for personal growth\nand therapy.\n[...]\nDirections of Integration and Disintegration\n[...]\nEach type has specific behavioral patterns in stress\n(Disintegration) and security (Integration), denoted by\nconnections between types. Understanding these patterns\nallows for deeper personal insight and offers pathways for\ndevelopment.\n\n---\n\nTitle: N/A\nURL: https://ia600405.us.archive.org/27/items/TheWisdomOfTheEnneagram.TheCompleteGuideToPsychologicalAndSpiritualGrowthForTheN/The%20Wisdom%20of%20the%20Enneagram.%20The%20Complete%20Guide%20to%20Psychological%20and%20Spiritual%20Growth%20for%20the%20Nine%20Personality%20Types%20by%20Don%20Richard%20Riso%20and%20Russ%20Hudson.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nNine Personality Types\n[...]\nDON RICHARD RISO and RUSS HUDSON\n[...]\nLntroducing the NineTypes 10\n[...]\n5 The Triadic Self 49\n[...]\nThe Triads 49\n[...]\n6 Dynamics and Variations 69\n[...]\nThe Wings 69\n[...]\n70\n[...]\nThe Levels ofDevelopment 75\n[...]\nThe Directions ofIntegration\n[...]\nandDisintegration 87\n[...]\nII T THE NINE PERSONALITY TYPES 95\n[...]\n7 Type One: THE REFORMER 97\n[...]\n8 Type Two: THE HELPER 125\n[...]\n9 Type Three: THE ACHIEVER 151\n[...]\n10 Type Four: THE INDIVIDUALIST 178\n[...]\n11 Type Five: THE INVESTIGATOR 206\n[...]\n13 Type Seven: THE ENTHUSIAST 260\n[...]\n14 Type Eight: THE CHALLENGER 287\n[...]\n15 Type Nine: THE PEACEMAKER 314\n[...]\nTHE ENNEAGRAM (pronounced \"ANY-a-gram\") isa geometric figure\n[...]\nthat maps out the nine fundamental personality types of human nature\n[...]\nand their complex interrelationships. It is a development of modern\n[...]\npsychology that has roots in spiritual wisdom from many different an\n[...]\ncient traditions.- The word Enneagram comes from the Greek for\n[...]\n\"nine\"—ennea—and \"figure\"—grammos; thus, it isa \"nine-pointed fig\u0002ure.\n[...]\nINTRODUCING THE NINE TYPES\n[...]\nWhile we will recognize in ourselves behaviors of all nine types,\n[...]\nour most defining characteristics are rooted in one of these types. On\n[...]\npage 13 you will find a questionnaire, the Riso-Hudson QUEST, that\n[...]\ncan help you narrow down your basic type, and at the beginning of\n[...]\neach type chapter there is a second independent test, the Riso-Hudson\n[...]\nTAS or Type Attitude Sorter, to help you check your findings.\n[...]\nType One: TheReformer. The principled, idealistic type. Ones are\n[...]\nType Two: The Helper. The caring, interpersonal type. Twos are\n[...]\nType Three: The Achiever. The adaptable, success-oriented type.\n[...]\nType Four: The Individualist. The romantic, introspective type.\n[...]\nType Five: The Investigator. The intense, cerebral\n[...]\nType Six: The Loyalist. The committed, security-oriented type.\n[...]\nType Seven: The Enthusiast. The busy, productive type. Sevens are\n[...]\nType Eight: The Challenger. The powerful, dominating type.\n[...]\nType Nine: The Peacemaker. The easygoing, self-effacing type.\n[...]\nbut can also be too willing to go\n[...]\nThe first questionnaire, which follows on pages 14-15, is the Riso\u0002Hudson QUEST, the\n[...]\nThe secondset of questionnaires is the Riso-Hudson TAS,\n[...]\nA major breakthrough camein 1977when he discovered the Levels\n[...]\nof Development. The Levels revealed the gradations of growth and de\n[...]\nterioration that people actually move through in their lives. They\n[...]\nshowed which traits and motivations wentwith which types, and why.\n[...]\nMost profoundly, they indicated the degrees of our identification with\n[...]\nHe also empha\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Centers of Intelligence: Head, Heart, Gut\nURL: https://enneagramuserguide.com/enneagram-guide/enneagram-centers\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram centers, sometimes referred to as \" the triads,\" define three types of intelligence we use to process or relate to the world: the head, the heart, and the gut. Each of the nine Enneagram personality types is preoccupied more with one center than the other two.\n[...]\nThe three centers of intelligence for the Enneagram types are commonly called the head or head-based center, the heart of heart-based center, and the gut or body-based center.\n[...]\nThe types pointed to by the triangle on the Enneagram symbol (3, 6, and 9) lie in the middle of each center. The types on either side of 3, 6, and 9 make up the two other types in those centers.\n[...]\n- 567: Head or Head-Based Types\n- 234: Heart or Heart-Based Types\n- 891: Gut or Body-Based Types\n[...]\ndeficiency for not living up to a\n[...]\nidealized sense of self.\n[...]\nThe anger triad consists of types 8, 9, and 1. Anger for these types involves the gut or body center. It can be thought of as an energy of will that pushes against obstacles to create movement or resists being pushed.\n[...]\nThe Enne\n[...]\ntypes evolved from\n[...]\nIchazo's ego-types which represented nine types of\n[...]\nfixation. Although an individual would identify a single fixation to work on, a more complete approach was to identify one fixation from each of the three centers. This was called a person's tri-fix.\n[...]\nany trademark or copyright issues\n[...]\nthe tri-center approach.\n[...]\nWith the tri-center approach, as applied to the Enneagram personality types, an individual identifies a dominant gut type, heart type, and head type. There can also be an order of preference for those three dominant types or centers as well.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram personality types group the nine types into three centers of intelligence often referred to as the gut, heart, and head centers.\n[...]\nDominant Type in Each Center with Wings Test This test determines your dominant type in each center (aka tri-center, trifix, tritype, truetype) along with the wings of those types.Use when you want to know your tri-center or tri-center with wings.\n[...]\n- Enneagram Type Preference Test This test produces a scored list of all nine types.Questions are forced-choice, similar to the method used by the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indictor (RHETI).Use to determine type, wings, gut/heart/head types, and tri-center.\n- Center Type Comparison Test This test scores the three types in a given center to determine your dominant type within that center (gut, heart, or head type).Use when you don't know your dominant type for one of the centers.\n[...]\n- primary type\n- candidate types\n- preferred wing\n- intinctual subtype\n- instinctual variant stacking\n- center types (gut, heart, and head)\n- tri-center with wings\n\n---\n\nTitle: Levels of Development - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/levels-of-development/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThere is an internal structure within each personality type. That structure is the continuum of behaviors, attitudes, defenses, and motivations formed by the nine Levels of Development which make up the personality type itself. This discovery (and the working out of all the traits that comprise each type) was originally made by Don Riso in 1977, and was further developed by Don with Russ Hudson in the 1990s. They are the only Enneagram teachers to include this important factor in their treatment of the Enneagram. The Levels are an important contribution not only to the Enneagram but to ego psychology — and the personality types of the Enneagram cannot be adequately explained without them. The Levels account for differences among people of the same type as well as how people change for better or for worse. The Levels can also help therapists and counselors pinpoint what is actually going on with clients and suggest solutions to the problems they may be confronting.\n[...]\nby understanding the\n[...]\n, one can see\n[...]\n—and how\n[...]\nnoted, without the Levels, the Enneagram is\n[...]\nThe continuum is comprised of nine internal Levels of Development—briefly, there are three Levels in the healthy section, three Levels in the average section, and three Levels in the unhealthy section. It may help you to think of the continuum of Levels as a photographer’s gray scale which has gradations from pure white to pure black with many shades of gray in between. On the continuum, the healthiest traits appear first, at the top, so to speak. As we move down the continuum in a spiral pattern, we progressively pass through each Level of Development marking a distinct shift in the personality’s deterioration to the pure black of psychological breakdown at the bottom. The continuum for each of the personality types can be seen in the following diagram.\n[...]\n- Level 4: The Level of Imbalance/ Social Role\n- Level 5: The Level of Interpersonal Control\n- Level 6: The Level of Overcompensation\n[...]\n- Level 7: The Level of Violation\n- Level 8: The Level of Obsession and Compulsion\n- Level 9: The Level of Pathological Destructiveness\n[...]\nBy contrast, the movement\n[...]\nhealth, up the Levels, is simultaneous with being more present and awake in our minds, hearts, and bodies. As we become more present, we become less fixated in\n[...]\ndefensive structures of our personality and are more attuned and open to ourselves and our environment. We see our personality objectively in action rather than “falling asleep” to our\n[...]\n“not doing” our personality and of gaining some real distance from\n\n---\n\nTitle: Levels of Development\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/levels/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe framework that names this difference is the Levels of Development, a nine-level scale developed by Don Riso in 1977 and refined with Russ Hudson through the 1990s. The framework describes how each Enneagram type expresses itself across a range from psychological liberation at the top to pathological constriction at the bottom. Same type, nine different qualities of expression.\n[...]\nThis page covers the structure of the\n[...]\n, the three\n[...]\n, what each\n[...]\ninteract with the other Enneagram elements (\n[...]\n, lines, subtypes\n[...]\nof working with levels in self-observation.\n[...]\nThe Levels of Development are nine levels, grouped into three bands of three levels each:\n[...]\n- Healthy: Levels 1, 2, 3\n- Average: Levels 4, 5, 6\n- Unhealthy: Levels 7, 8, 9\n[...]\nruns from highest functioning\n[...]\nmost constricted (Level 9\n[...]\nhas a structural-function name — describing what the ego is doing at that level, what defense mechanism is operating, what relationship to one\n[...]\n| Level | Name | Band | |---|---|---| | 1 | The Level of Liberation | Healthy | | 2 | The Level of Psychological Capacity | Healthy | | 3 | The Level of Social Value | Healthy | | 4 | The Level of Imbalance / Social Role | Average | | 5 | The Level of Interpersonal Control | Average | | 6 | The Level of Overcompensation | Average | | 7 | The Level of Violation | Unhealthy | | 8 | The Level of Obsession and Compulsion | Unhealthy | | 9 | The Level of Pathological Destructiveness | Unhealthy |\n[...]\nThis is the most concrete interaction. The Riso-Hudson framing is that stress-direction movement (along the disintegration line) tends to be activated at average-to-unhealthy levels, while growth-direction movement (along the integration line) tends to be accessed at healthy levels. A Type 1 at average levels begins exhibiting average-to-unhealthy Type 4 patterns under sustained pressure (moodiness, brooding, self-absorption). A Type 1 at healthy levels accesses healthy Type 7 patterns spontaneously (lightness, openness, spontaneity).\n[...]\nThe contribution of the wing also shifts by level. At healthy levels, a person can access the gifts of their wing as additional resource. At average levels, the wing's coloration is most visible — this is where 5w4s look distinctively different from 5w6s. At unhealthy levels, the wing's constrictions compound the type's, sometimes producing the most difficult-to-distinguish presentations.\n[...]\nWings describe steady-state coloration: how the core type expresses itself flavored by the adjacent type. Wings are about ongoing presentation.\n[...]\nLevels describe vertical functioning: how integrated or constricted the type expression is at a given time. Levels are about quality of expression.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Triads: Centers (Mind, Heart, Gut) and Others - Personality Science\nURL: https://enneagramtest.net/personality/enneagram/triads/\nPublished: 2023-07-01T18:15:44.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram contains many kinds of triads, which is a group of three. The main triads of the Enneagram are based on the three centers of intelligence: mind, heart, and gut (or body), which give rise to the thinking, feeling, and instinctive triads.\n[...]\nAll 9 Enneagram types are divided into three triads based on these centers, and each type reflects the emotions and issues of its respective center in a unique way. Those triads are:\n[...]\n- Mind: Types 5, 6, 7\n- Heart: Types 2, 3, 4\n- Body/Gut: Types 8, 9, 1\n[...]\n. This results in a fear about the future and not having\n[...]\nneeds to be\n[...]\n. The three\n[...]\nof the heart triad are\n[...]\nGut Center: Instinct\n[...]\nThe gut or body center is responsible for instinct, and particularly for planning for the future. This results in a preoccupation with boundaries, and anger from boundaries being transgressed or violated. The three types of the gut triad are 8, 9, and 1, and each type experiences the gut center differently and deals with its issues in a particular way:\n[...]\n6, 7\n[...]\nHeart | 2, 3, 4\n[...]\n| Shame | Image |\n[...]\n| Gut / Body | 8, 9, 1 | Instinctive | Anger | Autonomy |\n[...]\nThe Object Relations triads are based on three particular object relations, which Don Riso called “Dominant Affects”:\n[...]\n- Attachment (Type 3, 6, 9): The “positive” object relation that one feels in relationship with another person when one’s needs are being met. This was called the “central” object relation by object relations theorists.\n- Rejection (Types 2, 5, 8): The object relation that results from one’s emotional needs being disregarded or rejected.\n- Frustration (Types 1, 4, 7): The object relation that results from one’s emotional needs being inconsistently or unreliably met.\n[...]\n1, 2,\n[...]\n(inner critics). Compliant types are sometimes called Dutiful\n[...]\n. The superego represent the internalized\n[...]\n- Assertive\n[...]\nTypes 3, 7, 8.\n[...]\n: Types 4, 5, 9.\n[...]\n| Enneagram Type | Center | Relation to Center | Object Relations | Harmonics | Hornevian Group |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Type 1 | Gut | Under-express | Frustration | Competency | Compliant |\n| Type 2 | Heart | Over-express | Rejection | Positive Outlook | Compliant |\n| Type 3 | Heart | Repress | Attachment | Competency | Assertive |\n| Type 4 | Heart | Under-express | Frustration | Reactive | Withdrawn |\n| Type 5 | Mind | Over-express | Rejection | Competency | Withdrawn |\n| Type 6 | Mind | Repress | Attachment | Reactive | Compliant |\n| Type 7 | Mind | Under-express | Frustration | Positive Outlook | Assertive |\n| Type 8 | Gut | Over-express | Rejection | Reactive | Assertive |\n| Type 9 | Gut | Repress | Attachment | Positive Outlook | Withdrawn |","_meta":{"searchTime":1453.6}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_nayathjv684y_3","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: The Enneagram: A systematic review of the literature and directions for future research\nURL: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jclp.23097\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Arthur, K. B.\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram is a typology that many clients use to understand their personality and interpersonal patterns, despite some concerns about its validity. Thus, the purpose of this review is to provide a comprehensive and clinician-friendly review of the extant empirical work on the Enneagram. After reviewing 104 independent samples, we found mixed evidence of reliability and validity. In terms of strengths, some factor analytic work has shown partial alignment with prior theorizing, and subscales show theory-consistent relationships with other constructs such as the Big 5. Also, several studies found the Enneagram was helpful for personal/spiritual growth. However, factor analytic work has typically found fewer than nine factors, and no work has used clustering techniques to derive the nine types. Also, there is little research supporting secondary aspects of Enneagram theory, such as wings and intertype movement. We conclude by highlighting directions for future research and implications for clinical practice.\n[...]\nyer, J. J.(2001).\n[...]\nof the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator. California Institute of Integral Studies, San Francisco, CA.\n[...]\n* Gamard, W. S.(1986).*Interrater reliability and validity of judgments of enneagram personality types*(Unpublished doctoral dissertation). California Institute of Integral Studies, San Francisco, CA.\n[...]\nNewgent, R. A.(2001).An investigation of the reliability and\n[...]\nof the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator. The University of Akron, Akron, OH.\n[...]\n* Newgent, R. A.,\n[...]\narr, P. E.,Newman,\n[...]\n, K. K\n[...]\n200\n[...]\niso-Hudson enneagram type indicator\n[...]\nin Counseling and Development*,36,226–237.\n[...]\n* Scott, S. A.(2011).*An analysis of the validity of the Enneagram*(Unpublished doctoral dissertation). College of William and Mary, Williamsburg, VA.\n[...]\nSharp, P. M.(199\n[...]\ndissertation). Texas Tech University\n[...]\nSiudzinski, R. M.(1995).*Unpublished\n[...]\nstudy*. (Reported in\n[...]\n* Stevens, K. L.(2011).*Comparisons of\n[...]\nneagram types and five-factor model traits of graduate psychology students*(Unpublished doctoral dissertation). The Chicago School of Professional Psychology, Chicago, IL.\n[...]\n* Sutton, A.(2012).“But is\n[...]\nreal?” A review of research on the Enneagram.*Enneagram Journal*,5,5–20.\n[...]\n* Wagner, J. P.(1981). A descriptive, reliability, and validity study of the enneagram personality typology (Unpublished doctoral dissertation). Loyola University, Chicago, IL.\n[...]\ntypology: The enneagram.*Journal of Clinical Psychology*,39,712–717.\n[...]\n* Warling, D. L.(199\n[...]\nof the Riso Hudson Enneagram type indicator (RHETI)*(Unpublished doctoral dissertation). The University of Guelph, Guelph, ON.\n\n---\n\nTitle: The reliability and validity of the Open Enneagram of Personality Scales\nURL: https://opis-cdn.tinkoffjournal.ru/mercury/enneagramma-1.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Kayleigh Kastelein\nHighlights:\nThe purpose of this study is to assess the reliability and validity of the 36-item Open \nEnneagram of Personality Scales (OEPS). Our general hypothesis was that the OEPS \nwould show adequate reliability evidence but not validity evidence. Participants were\n[...]\nwhile internal consistency reliability, factor analysis, and correlations with the Big Five \nInventory (BFI; John, Donahue, & Kentle) were done using 1039 participants. An average\n[...]\nPearson’s correlation of .68 (range: 0.54 - 0.75) showed inadequate test-retest reliability\n[...]\ninternal consistency of the OEPS factors. Confirmatory factor analysis found insufficient\n[...]\nevidence for the OEPS (χ2 = 1255, p < .001, CFI = 0.56, TLI = 0.50, and RMSEA = 0.08).\n[...]\nbetween the OEPS and BFI that were to be expected but were not supported in this study’s\n[...]\nanalysis which is most likely due to the lack of strong psychometric support for the OEPS.\n[...]\nOverall, this study showed OEPS did not show strong reliability or validity evidence.\n[...]\nThere is still some debate\n[...]\nThere have been recent efforts to address these uncertainties by gaining psychometric \nevidence for the Enneagram, but there remains inconsistent and inadequate research on\n[...]\nthe reliability and validity of the Enneagram (Bland 2010; Matise, 2007). This study will \nattempt to address this lack of psychometric support of the Enneagram.\n[...]\nrelationships with Enneagram types. A second method to assess the validity of the is by\n[...]\nexamining its internal structure using factor analysis. This study will focus on\n[...]\nconfirmatory factor analysis which attempts to see how well the data fits the given model \n(Navarro & Foxcroft, 2019). When studying the Enneagram, factor analysis would look\n[...]\ninternal structure of the OEPS, this study will perform confirmatory factor analysis on\n[...]\nOEPS responses. Because the Enneagram theory contains nine types, the OEPS should\n[...]\nBig Five Inventory \nThe Big Five Inventory (BFI) was used to obtain the convergent validity of the \nOEPS. It was created by John, Donahue, and Kentle (1991) as a shorter alternative to a\n[...]\nWhen correlated to other major Big Five personality tests, the BFI correlated strongly to\n[...]\nevidence from confirmatory factor analysis with all items correlating over .90 to the\n[...]\nfactors (John & Srivastava, 1999).\n[...]\nFactor Analysis \nConfirmatory factor analysis (CFA) was performed on all 36 OEPS items. Items \nwere put into factors based on the question that was intended for that factor. The analysis \nwas performed on time 1 responses with 1,039 participants. The results showed that a 9-\n[...]\nfactor model was not a strong fit for the model (CFI = .56, TLI = .50, and RMSEA = .08).\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Scientific Validity: Peer-Reviewed Evidence – Cogn-IQ.org\nURL: https://www.cogn-iq.org/blog/enneagram-validity/\nPublished: 2024-02-12T10:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Priya Sharma, Ph.D. \n\t\t\t\t\t · 13 min read \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t UPDATED 19 May 2026\nHighlights:\nThe most comprehensive recent treatment of the Enneagram’s empirical status is Hook, Hall, Davis, Van Tongeren, and Conner’s (2020) systematic review in the Journal of Clinical Psychology. They examined 104 empirical studies of the Enneagram and concluded that despite its widespread practitioner use, the framework has “limited evidence of validity” in the peer-reviewed literature. Their review identified four core problems: (1) inconsistent factor structure across studies, (2) overlap with the Big Five dimensions, (3) thin criterion-related validity, and (4) a research base dominated by sympathetic researchers rather than independent replication. The sections below walk through each problem area in turn.\n[...]\nThe evidence here is not encouraging. Studies using exploratory factor analysis(EFA) on Enneagram instruments have generally failed to recover a clean nine-factor structure. Newgent, Parr, Newman, and Higgins (2004) administered the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI) and found that factor analysis did not yield the expected nine-factor solution. Instead, the factors that emerged bore closer resemblance to established Big Five dimensions than to the nine Enneagram types.\n[...]\nDameyer (2001) found some support for the type structure in a sample of 688 participants using the RHETI, but the factor structure was not clean—several types showed substantial cross- loadings and poor discriminant validity. The nine types did not emerge as clearly separable dimensions in the way that the Big Five consistently do across samples, languages, and cultures.\n[...]\nA caveat: pro-Enneagram sources sometimes cite Cronbach’s alpha values of around .80–.90 for individual RHETI subscales as evidence that the instrument is “scientifically valid”. This conflates two different things. High internal consistency means that items within a scale correlate with each other, which can happen even when the scale is measuring a Big Five trait rather than a distinct Enneagram type. As Hook et al. (2020) emphasised, internal-consistency reliability is a precondition for validity but is not itself evidence of validity, particularly construct validity, which is where the Enneagram literature is thinnest.\n[...]\n| Cross-cultural replication | Very limited | Replicated in 50+ cultures (McCrae, and Terracciano, 2005) |\n[...]\nThe Enneagram has very limited peer-reviewed validation. Its nine-type structure has not been consistently replicated in factor-analytic studies. No meta-analysis demonstrates criterion-related validity for predicting job performance or other real-world outcomes. The Enneagram’s types overlap substantially with Big Five dimensions, which have far stronger validity evidence (Newgent et al., 2004).\n\n---\n\nTitle: “BUT IS IT REAL?”A REVIEW OF RESEARCH ON THE ENNEAGRAM\nURL: https://ieaninepoints.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2012-IEA-Journal_Anna-Sutton.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n(Sutton, 2007\n[...]\nmodel as a whole\n[...]\nQuestionnaires tested against self-identified type\n[...]\nidentified some of\n[...]\nwas that there were statistically significant differences between the types on the scales from these different personality questionnaires, indicating that the Enneagram\n[...]\nThe Enneagram as a theory of personality In summary, the research we have so far gives us a good indication that the Enneagram could fulfil the three criteria personality psychologists are looking for: we can make clear, testable hypotheses from it, it is practically useful and it is comprehensive. In practical terms, this is what we have learnt from the research: The personality types described by the Enneagram can be clearly differentiated from each other using other established personality measures. (For an example, see the table which summarises findings on the Big Five.) Enneagram personality questionnaires like the RHETI and WEPSS are reasonably reliable but we should still be cautious about their validity. That means, we’re likely to get the same results on different occasions but there’s no guarantee that’s really our type. The types are reasonably equally distributed in the population, though there are some small differences. Trained practitioners are pretty good at typing people in interview, but not as good as they think they are!\n[...]\nSummary of the Enneagram Type scores on the Big Five Three studies used the Big Five (Sutton, 2007, Newgent et al., 2004, Brown and Bartram, 2005) to investigate the Enneagram types, which means that we can start to see what trait profile is typical for each of the nine types. The following are brief definitions of the traits. It should be remembered that just like no Enneagram type is “better” or “worse” than any of the others, neither are different scores on these traits. Extraversion: people scoring at the higher end tend to be outgoing, sociable and confident, while those at the lower end are more reserved, independent and private. Agreeableness: higher scores indicate that people are trusting, altruistic and will tend to go along with those around them, while lower scores indicate that people are more sceptical, self-focused and tough-minded. Conscientiousness: those at the higher end are more dutiful, organised and disciplined, while those at the lower end are likely to be more disorganised and spontaneous. Emotional Stability: high scores indicate people are secure, calm and unflappable while lower scores indicate people are excitable, emotionally reactive and alert. Openness to Experience: people scoring high on this trait tend to be curious, liberal and novelty-seeking, while those at the lower end are more practical and conservative.\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Enneagram: A Review of the Empirical and Transformational Literature\nURL: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271180874_The_Enneagram_A_Review_of_the_Empirical_and_Transformational_Literature\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n... Enneagram mizaç modeli ile ilgili en temel kısıtlılık bilimsel kanıtlara dayanmıyor oluşundan gelmektedir. Çoğunlukla bireysel deneyimler ve öznel yorumlamalar ile şekillenen Enneagram'ın, kişilik ölçüm aracı olarak değerlendirilebilmesinin geçerlilik ve güvenilirlik aşamalarından geçmesine bağlı olduğu belirtilmiştir(Bland, 2010). ...\n[...]\ninventory and examine its construct validity. Enneagram analysis temperament\n[...]\ninadequate items and have low reliability levels. In this study, Enneagram modelling\n[...]\nomitted. By this way, the concept was measured by 81 items. Factor analysis was\n[...]\nperformed for every temperament dimension. Alpha values for temperament\n[...]\ndimensions range from 0.73 (Temperament 5) and 0.82 (Temperament 1) and alpha\n[...]\nvalue for total 81 items is 0.87. The data were gathered 1162 respondents lend color\n[...]\nto validity and reliability of both the 9 temperaments separately with its total 81\n[...]\npersonality prediction systems studies\n[...]\ninformative personality model\n[...]\nunderstanding. The\n[...]\nprediction system is presented\n[...]\ndoes not require\n[...]\nprediction of the\n[...]\nstatistical method. The\n[...]\nUnderstanding people’s emotions and orientations attracts researchers nowadays\n[...]\nresearch concentrates on models\n[...]\nthan these models\n[...]\nA proposed case study\n[...]\nThe Reformer, Type\n[...]\nThe Helper, Type\n[...]\nAchiever, Type 4\n[...]\nThe Individualist, Type\n[...]\nThe Investigator, Type 6-The Loyalist, Type 7-The Enthusiast, Type 8-The Challenger, and Type\n[...]\n-The Peacemaker (Riso & Hudson\n[...]\n08). Enneagram is a scientifically proven model\n[...]\nother(Bland,\n[...]\n2010), and each type perceives the world differently (Riso & Hudson, 1999). One of the potentially promising features of the Enneagram is that it describes the behavior and developmental levels of individuals in situations of stress and growth (Sutton et al., 2013).\n[...]\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator: Estimates of Reliability and Validity\n[...]\n* Jan 2004\n* Rebecca A. Newgent\n* P.E. Parr\n* Isadore Newman\n* Kristin K. Higgins\nThis investigation was conducted to estimate the reliability and validity of scores on the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (D. R. Riso & R. Hudson, 1999a). Results of 287 participants were analyzed. Alpha suggests an adequate degree of internal consistency. Evidence provides mixed support for construct validity using correlational and canonical analyses but strong support for heuristic value.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Is the Enneagram reliable? What the evidence says - bridge dissemination\nURL: https://bridgepsych.info/is-the-enneagram-reliable-what-the-evidence-says/\nPublished: 2025-03-28T03:38:50.000Z\nAuthor: Dr. Matt B\nHighlights:\nWhen it comes to psychological tests, they need to be reliable in order to be accurate. We again use reliability in a nerdy way: the test itself demonstrates a similar result when repeated over time, between individuals, or in other ways. The Enneagram is a popular test of personality, but how do assessment experts view it? Is the Enneagram reliable? And what does that mean for valid results?\n[...]\nMany settings, from counseling practices to business organizations, use the test. So it has done well in a marketing sense, but is the Enneagram reliable? Research finds the test has questionnable reliability and validity. Therefore, it is not approved by most testing experts.\n[...]\nThis is for a few reasons. First, the nine categories were created by reasoned explanations and were not tested psychometrically. Psychometric testing is an important step in developing psychological tests because it examines how test items relate to validated psychological concepts and to other related validated tests.\n[...]\nSecond, research conducted on the existing Enneagram test finds mixed results, at best. Importantly, the test does not demonstrate reliability across studies. That is, it does not consistently generate similar scores over time or across individuals. So you could give it to the same person multiple times or across groups of people and it’s scores will not stay relatively consistent.\n[...]\nThe need to replicate results consistently is important for ensuring we know that a test measures what it says it measures. This is a test’s validity. If a test cannot demonstrate similarity in measurements over time, then it is difficult to know whether it measures what proposes it measures. That is, it could be measuring something completely different than it claims to measure. The Myer’s Briggs personality test demonstrates similar concerns for reliability and validity.\n[...]\ntell clients to\n[...]\n“with a grain of\n[...]\nThe lack of known\n[...]\ndiagnostic utility from\n[...]\nSo if the Enneagram is reliable also affects whether it is valid. When a test claims to measure a certain “thing” or phenomenon, it should pick up on the presence of that thing in the same way each time it measures it. Unfortunately, the Enneagram does not appear to do so.\n[...]\nOther, professionally sought-after personality tests do show high reliability and validity. The Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (now in its 3rd version, MMPI-3) and the Personality Assessment Inventory (PAI) both do so. They also both map on to clinical concepts well. Both tests require some training to understand, but also have online services that help analyze and explain results.\n[...]\npopularity and appeal\n[...]\npeople like it\n[...]\nwe can help"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"sessi