is found insufficient\n[...]\nevidence for the OEPS (χ2 = 1255, p < .001, CFI = 0.56, TLI = 0.50, and RMSEA = 0.08).\n[...]\nbetween the OEPS and BFI that were to be expected but were not supported in this study’s\n[...]\nanalysis which is most likely due to the lack of strong psychometric support for the OEPS.\n[...]\nOverall, this study showed OEPS did not show strong reliability or validity evidence.\n[...]\nThere is still some debate\n[...]\nThere have been recent efforts to address these uncertainties by gaining psychometric \nevidence for the Enneagram, but there remains inconsistent and inadequate research on\n[...]\nthe reliability and validity of the Enneagram (Bland 2010; Matise, 2007). This study will \nattempt to address this lack of psychometric support of the Enneagram.\n[...]\nrelationships with Enneagram types. A second method to assess the validity of the is by\n[...]\nexamining its internal structure using factor analysis. This study will focus on\n[...]\nconfirmatory factor analysis which attempts to see how well the data fits the given model \n(Navarro & Foxcroft, 2019). When studying the Enneagram, factor analysis would look\n[...]\ninternal structure of the OEPS, this study will perform confirmatory factor analysis on\n[...]\nOEPS responses. Because the Enneagram theory contains nine types, the OEPS should\n[...]\nBig Five Inventory \nThe Big Five Inventory (BFI) was used to obtain the convergent validity of the \nOEPS. It was created by John, Donahue, and Kentle (1991) as a shorter alternative to a\n[...]\nWhen correlated to other major Big Five personality tests, the BFI correlated strongly to\n[...]\nevidence from confirmatory factor analysis with all items correlating over .90 to the\n[...]\nfactors (John & Srivastava, 1999).\n[...]\nFactor Analysis \nConfirmatory factor analysis (CFA) was performed on all 36 OEPS items. Items \nwere put into factors based on the question that was intended for that factor. The analysis \nwas performed on time 1 responses with 1,039 participants. The results showed that a 9-\n[...]\nfactor model was not a strong fit for the model (CFI = .56, TLI = .50, and RMSEA = .08).\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Scientific Validity: Peer-Reviewed Evidence – Cogn-IQ.org\nURL: https://www.cogn-iq.org/blog/enneagram-validity/\nPublished: 2024-02-12T10:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Priya Sharma, Ph.D. \n\t\t\t\t\t · 13 min read \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t UPDATED 19 May 2026\nHighlights:\nThe most comprehensive recent treatment of the Enneagram’s empirical status is Hook, Hall, Davis, Van Tongeren, and Conner’s (2020) systematic review in the Journal of Clinical Psychology. They examined 104 empirical studies of the Enneagram and concluded that despite its widespread practitioner use, the framework has “limited evidence of validity” in the peer-reviewed literature. Their review identified four core problems: (1) inconsistent factor structure across studies, (2) overlap with the Big Five dimensions, (3) thin criterion-related validity, and (4) a research base dominated by sympathetic researchers rather than independent replication. The sections below walk through each problem area in turn.\n[...]\nThe evidence here is not encouraging. Studies using exploratory factor analysis(EFA) on Enneagram instruments have generally failed to recover a clean nine-factor structure. Newgent, Parr, Newman, and Higgins (2004) administered the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI) and found that factor analysis did not yield the expected nine-factor solution. Instead, the factors that emerged bore closer resemblance to established Big Five dimensions than to the nine Enneagram types.\n[...]\nDameyer (2001) found some support for the type structure in a sample of 688 participants using the RHETI, but the factor structure was not clean—several types showed substantial cross- loadings and poor discriminant validity. The nine types did not emerge as clearly separable dimensions in the way that the Big Five consistently do across samples, languages, and cultures.\n[...]\nA caveat: pro-Enneagram sources sometimes cite Cronbach’s alpha values of around .80–.90 for individual RHETI subscales as evidence that the instrument is “scientifically valid”. This conflates two different things. High internal consistency means that items within a scale correlate with each other, which can happen even when the scale is measuring a Big Five trait rather than a distinct Enneagram type. As Hook et al. (2020) emphasised, internal-consistency reliability is a precondition for validity but is not itself evidence of validity, particularly construct validity, which is where the Enneagram literature is thinnest.\n[...]\n| Cross-cultural replication | Very limited | Replicated in 50+ cultures (McCrae, and Terracciano, 2005) |\n[...]\nThe Enneagram has very limited peer-reviewed validation. Its nine-type structure has not been consistently replicated in factor-analytic studies. No meta-analysis demonstrates criterion-related validity for predicting job performance or other real-world outcomes. The Enneagram’s types overlap substantially with Big Five dimensions, which have far stronger validity evidence (Newgent et al., 2004).\n\n---\n\nTitle: “BUT IS IT REAL?”A REVIEW OF RESEARCH ON THE ENNEAGRAM\nURL: https://ieaninepoints.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2012-IEA-Journal_Anna-Sutton.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n(Sutton, 2007\n[...]\nmodel as a whole\n[...]\nQuestionnaires tested against self-identified type\n[...]\nidentified some of\n[...]\nwas that there were statistically significant differences between the types on the scales from these different personality questionnaires, indicating that the Enneagram\n[...]\nThe Enneagram as a theory of personality In summary, the research we have so far gives us a good indication that the Enneagram could fulfil the three criteria personality psychologists are looking for: we can make clear, testable hypotheses from it, it is practically useful and it is comprehensive. In practical terms, this is what we have learnt from the research: The personality types described by the Enneagram can be clearly differentiated from each other using other established personality measures. (For an example, see the table which summarises findings on the Big Five.) Enneagram personality questionnaires like the RHETI and WEPSS are reasonably reliable but we should still be cautious about their validity. That means, we’re likely to get the same results on different occasions but there’s no guarantee that’s really our type. The types are reasonably equally distributed in the population, though there are some small differences. Trained practitioners are pretty good at typing people in interview, but not as good as they think they are!\n[...]\nSummary of the Enneagram Type scores on the Big Five Three studies used the Big Five (Sutton, 2007, Newgent et al., 2004, Brown and Bartram, 2005) to investigate the Enneagram types, which means that we can start to see what trait profile is typical for each of the nine types. The following are brief definitions of the traits. It should be remembered that just like no Enneagram type is “better” or “worse” than any of the others, neither are different scores on these traits. Extraversion: people scoring at the higher end tend to be outgoing, sociable and confident, while those at the lower end are more reserved, independent and private. Agreeableness: higher scores indicate that people are trusting, altruistic and will tend to go along with those around them, while lower scores indicate that people are more sceptical, self-focused and tough-minded. Conscientiousness: those at the higher end are more dutiful, organised and disciplined, while those at the lower end are likely to be more disorganised and spontaneous. Emotional Stability: high scores indicate people are secure, calm and unflappable while lower scores indicate people are excitable, emotionally reactive and alert. Openness to Experience: people scoring high on this trait tend to be curious, liberal and novelty-seeking, while those at the lower end are more practical and conservative.\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Enneagram: A Review of the Empirical and Transformational Literature\nURL: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271180874_The_Enneagram_A_Review_of_the_Empirical_and_Transformational_Literature\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n... Enneagram mizaç modeli ile ilgili en temel kısıtlılık bilimsel kanıtlara dayanmıyor oluşundan gelmektedir. Çoğunlukla bireysel deneyimler ve öznel yorumlamalar ile şekillenen Enneagram'ın, kişilik ölçüm aracı olarak değerlendirilebilmesinin geçerlilik ve güvenilirlik aşamalarından geçmesine bağlı olduğu belirtilmiştir(Bland, 2010). ...\n[...]\ninventory and examine its construct validity. Enneagram analysis temperament\n[...]\ninadequate items and have low reliability levels. In this study, Enneagram modelling\n[...]\nomitted. By this way, the concept was measured by 81 items. Factor analysis was\n[...]\nperformed for every temperament dimension. Alpha values for temperament\n[...]\ndimensions range from 0.73 (Temperament 5) and 0.82 (Temperament 1) and alpha\n[...]\nvalue for total 81 items is 0.87. The data were gathered 1162 respondents lend color\n[...]\nto validity and reliability of both the 9 temperaments separately with its total 81\n[...]\npersonality prediction systems studies\n[...]\ninformative personality model\n[...]\nunderstanding. The\n[...]\nprediction system is presented\n[...]\ndoes not require\n[...]\nprediction of the\n[...]\nstatistical method. The\n[...]\nUnderstanding people’s emotions and orientations attracts researchers nowadays\n[...]\nresearch concentrates on models\n[...]\nthan these models\n[...]\nA proposed case study\n[...]\nThe Reformer, Type\n[...]\nThe Helper, Type\n[...]\nAchiever, Type 4\n[...]\nThe Individualist, Type\n[...]\nThe Investigator, Type 6-The Loyalist, Type 7-The Enthusiast, Type 8-The Challenger, and Type\n[...]\n-The Peacemaker (Riso & Hudson\n[...]\n08). Enneagram is a scientifically proven model\n[...]\nother(Bland,\n[...]\n2010), and each type perceives the world differently (Riso & Hudson, 1999). One of the potentially promising features of the Enneagram is that it describes the behavior and developmental levels of individuals in situations of stress and growth (Sutton et al., 2013).\n[...]\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator: Estimates of Reliability and Validity\n[...]\n* Jan 2004\n* Rebecca A. Newgent\n* P.E. Parr\n* Isadore Newman\n* Kristin K. Higgins\nThis investigation was conducted to estimate the reliability and validity of scores on the Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (D. R. Riso & R. Hudson, 1999a). Results of 287 participants were analyzed. Alpha suggests an adequate degree of internal consistency. Evidence provides mixed support for construct validity using correlational and canonical analyses but strong support for heuristic value.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Is the Enneagram reliable? What the evidence says - bridge dissemination\nURL: https://bridgepsych.info/is-the-enneagram-reliable-what-the-evidence-says/\nPublished: 2025-03-28T03:38:50.000Z\nAuthor: Dr. Matt B\nHighlights:\nWhen it comes to psychological tests, they need to be reliable in order to be accurate. We again use reliability in a nerdy way: the test itself demonstrates a similar result when repeated over time, between individuals, or in other ways. The Enneagram is a popular test of personality, but how do assessment experts view it? Is the Enneagram reliable? And what does that mean for valid results?\n[...]\nMany settings, from counseling practices to business organizations, use the test. So it has done well in a marketing sense, but is the Enneagram reliable? Research finds the test has questionnable reliability and validity. Therefore, it is not approved by most testing experts.\n[...]\nThis is for a few reasons. First, the nine categories were created by reasoned explanations and were not tested psychometrically. Psychometric testing is an important step in developing psychological tests because it examines how test items relate to validated psychological concepts and to other related validated tests.\n[...]\nSecond, research conducted on the existing Enneagram test finds mixed results, at best. Importantly, the test does not demonstrate reliability across studies. That is, it does not consistently generate similar scores over time or across individuals. So you could give it to the same person multiple times or across groups of people and it’s scores will not stay relatively consistent.\n[...]\nThe need to replicate results consistently is important for ensuring we know that a test measures what it says it measures. This is a test’s validity. If a test cannot demonstrate similarity in measurements over time, then it is difficult to know whether it measures what proposes it measures. That is, it could be measuring something completely different than it claims to measure. The Myer’s Briggs personality test demonstrates similar concerns for reliability and validity.\n[...]\ntell clients to\n[...]\n“with a grain of\n[...]\nThe lack of known\n[...]\ndiagnostic utility from\n[...]\nSo if the Enneagram is reliable also affects whether it is valid. When a test claims to measure a certain “thing” or phenomenon, it should pick up on the presence of that thing in the same way each time it measures it. Unfortunately, the Enneagram does not appear to do so.\n[...]\nOther, professionally sought-after personality tests do show high reliability and validity. The Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (now in its 3rd version, MMPI-3) and the Personality Assessment Inventory (PAI) both do so. They also both map on to clinical concepts well. Both tests require some training to understand, but also have online services that help analyze and explain results.\n[...]\npopularity and appeal\n[...]\npeople like it\n[...]\nwe can help","_meta":{"searchTime":1138.3}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_nayathjv684y_4","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: About the RHETI® - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/rheti/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nAbout the RHETI® - The Enneagram Institute \n\n# The Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator(RHETI® version 2.5)\n\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5) is the world’s most popular Enneagram-based test. It is a scientifically validated, forced-choice personality test with 144 paired statements. The test takes about 40 minutes to complete.\n\nThe RHETI® version 2.5 has been independently scientifically validated. Rather than just indicating your basic type, it produces a full personality profile across all nine types. This provides you with a unique portrait, indicating the relative strengths and weaknesses of the nine types within your overall personality.\n\nThe RHETI® results are available in a PDF format and include your scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for your top three scores. These type descriptions have been revised and updated to provide the most comprehensive type summaries available.\n\n“We both felt the Enneagram as represented by The Enneagram Institute was a more efficacious measure of personality traits than any other, including the DiSC and Myers-Briggs.”\n\n> Mr. Kim and Ms. Janise Pries, El Paso, TexasDirector of Product Integrity and Reliability; Licensed Professional Counselor, Director of Guidance and Counseling\n\nQuestions? Please contact support@enneagraminstitute.com\n\nPURCHASE THE RHETI®\n\n---\n\nTitle: How The Enneagram System Works - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/how-the-enneagram-system-works/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe three Instincts (often erroneously\n[...]\n“the subtypes”) are a third set of distinctions that are extremely important for understanding personality. A major aspect of human nature lies in our instinctual “hard wiring” as biological beings. We each are endowed with specific instinctual intelligences that are necessary for our survival as individuals and as a\n[...]\n. We each have a self-preservation instinct (for preserving the body and its life and functioning), a sexual instinct (for extending ourselves in the environment and through the\n[...]\n), and a social instinct (for\n[...]\nThe Enneagram Institute® offers an online test, the Instinctual Variants Questionnaire (IVQ), for helping people determine not only their dominant instinct, but also their Instinctual Stack. The IVQ also provides a detailed personality profile derived from the combination of the test taker’s Enneagram type, wing, and Instinctual Stack.\n[...]\npeople are “nesters”—they seek domestic tranquility and security with a stable, reliable partner\n[...]\nSexual (aka “Attraction”) Instinct\n[...]\n, and tend to be more aggressive, competitive, charged, and emotionally intense than the Self-Pres or\n[...]\ntypes. Sexual\n[...]\nneed to have intense\n[...]\nor else they remain unsatisfied. They enjoy being intensely\n[...]\n—even merged—with\n[...]\n, and can become disenchanted with partners who are unable to meet their need for intense energetic union. Losing yourself in a “fusion” of being is the ideal here, and\n[...]\ntypes are always looking for this state with others and with stimulating objects in their world.\n[...]\nSocial (aka “Adaptive”) Instinct\n[...]\nJust as many people tend to misidentify themselves as Sexual types because they want one-on-one\n[...]\n, many people fail to recognize themselves as\n[...]\ntypes because they get the (false) idea\n[...]\n-Preservation types are interested in adjusting\n[...]\nenvironment to make themselves more\n[...]\nand comfortable,\n[...]\nthe needs of the\n[...]\n. Thus,\n[...]\nand attitudes are\n[...]\npeople and to be\n[...]\ntypes are the most concerned with\n[...]\nthat will have some impact on\n[...]\n, or even broader domains.\n[...]\ntend to be\n[...]\n, more open, engaging, and\n[...]\nresponsible than the other two types. In their primary relationships, they seek partners with whom they can share social activities, wanting their intimates to get involved in projects and events with them. Paradoxically, they actually tend to avoid long periods of exclusive intimacy and quiet solitude, seeing both as potentially limiting. Social types lose their sense of identity and meaning when they are not involved with others in activities that transcend their individual interests.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Get Started with Enneagram Tests - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/get-started-with-enneagram-tests/\nPublished: 2024-02-08T21:48:25.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nRHETI® – Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator\n[...]\n- A comprehensive, personalized PDF report\n- Your scores for all 9 Enneagram Types\n- Expanded Type descriptions for Your Top 3 Types\n- Detailed information on relationship issues, Type compatibility, personality dynamics, and the Levels of Development\n- Personal growth recommendations\n- No surprise monthly billing. One-time fee includes the test and detailed report.\n[...]\nThe IVQ is the first online test to measure our three basic instinctual intelligences: Self-preservation, Social, and Sexual. Find out which is dominant for you.\n[...]\n- A comprehensive, personalized PDF report\n- Your scores for all three Instincts: Self-preservation, Social, Sexual\n- In-depth information about the Instincts\n- Bonus content about the Instinctual Variants for your specific Enneagram Type\n- Personal growth recommendations\n[...]\nKnowing our Enneagram Type assists us with inner observation, self-knowledge, and personal growth. With our official, scientifically-validated Enneagram test, the Riso Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI®), you will receive a comprehensive, personalized Enneagram profile report with scores for all 9 Types, expanded Type descriptions for your top three Types, and much more.\n[...]\n### Our RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram Types\n[...]\nOur RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram\n[...]\nUse the RHETI (Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator) Enneagram Test and the IVQ (Instinctual Variant Questionnaire) with employees, clients, groups, and individuals to help them discover their Enneagram Type and learn about their Instincts. Volume discounts apply.\n[...]\n### Our RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram\n[...]\n- Includes detailed\n[...]\nRHETI® results are emailed to you in PDF format and include a test taker’s scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for the top three scores. IVQ results come in PDF format and include a test taker’s scores for all three Instincts, as well as general descriptions of the Instinctual Variants. Though knowledge of one’s primary Enneagram type is not necessary and does not affect the IVQ score, those who choose to enter their primary Enneagram type receive brief bonus content specific to their type.\n[...]\nOnce you have your RHETI® results, dive deeper by taking our Instinctual Variant Questionnaire, IVQ test. The Instinctual Variant Questionnaire (IVQ v2.0) will help you understand the role that all three Instincts play in your life. Once you have discovered your Instinctual Stack, you can understand your Enneagram type with even more depth and clarity.\n\n---\n\nTitle: RHETI Test | Russ Hudson\nURL: https://russhudson.com/rheti-test/\nPublished: 2020-06-02T16:35:03.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nRHETI Test | Russ Hudson\n\n## RHETI Test\n\n# Russ Hudson\n\n## The Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5)\n\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5) is the world’s most popular Enneagram-based test. It is a scientifically validated, forced-choice personality test with 144 paired statements. The test takes about 40 minutes to complete.\n\nThe RHETI® version 2.5 has been independently scientifically validated. Rather than just indicating your basic type, however, the RHETI® produces a full personality profile across all nine types. This provides you with a unique portrait, indicating the relative strengths and weaknesses of the nine types within your overall personality.\n\nThe RHETI® results are available in a PDF format and include your scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for your top three scores. These type descriptions have been revised and updated to provide the most comprehensive type summaries available.\n\n## Enjoy Russ' Free Monthly Presence Practice and other news.\n\n## Success! You have been added to our mailing list. Check your inbox or spam for your confirmation. Please mark the email as NOT SPAM and move to your inbox.\n\nFirst Name\n\nLast Name\n\nEmail\n\nSubscribe Now\n\nBy providing your email, you agree to receive our marketing materials, and we do not share your information with 3rd parties.\n\nRuss Hudson is a gifted teacher and wise scholar who offers some of the deepest and most comprehensive understanding of the transformative power of the enneagram. By helping me to become aware of the habitual patterns of thinking and acting that keep me a prisoner of my personality, his work has allowed me to live a more soul-directed life. The enneagram is complex and multi-dimensional, and I always look forward to hearing more from Russ about the unfolding nature of his beautiful work.\n\nCheryl Richardson\n\nAuthor of, Waking Up in Winter: In Search of What Really Matters at Midlife\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Instinctual Subtype Dimension of the Enneagram — Beatrice Chestnut\nURL: https://www.beatricechestnut.com/posts/instinctual-subtypes\nPublished: 2019-05-28T15:12:55.000Z\nAuthor: Written By  Amanda Braga\nHighlights:\nthe three “instincts” refer to our biological survival drives—those of 1.) Self-Preservation, 2.) Relating to others generally and in Social groups, and 3.) Sexual relationships, or One-to-One bonding, and other types of fusion experiences.\n[...]\nThe subtypes are the 27 personalities –more specific, more nuanced versions of the main type, with distinct traits and patterns–that you get when you multiply 3 x 9. Rather than being just “added” together — as in Type X + Instinct A = Type X who does Instinct A behaviors, the mixture of the main Type passion and patterns with a specific dominant instinct (and even mores an “instinct sequence” — which is first, second, and repressed — is more alchemical. The work of Claudio Naranjo in discerning and articulating these very accurate and revealing subtype descriptions, in my view, cannot be overstated.\n[...]\nto break into\n[...]\nby subtype, I saw that they had written on my piece of paper, “\n[...]\nTwo. I\n[...]\nthat the day\n[...]\n-Preservation\n[...]\n. I didn’t like that. I\n[...]\nthat’s not me…I’\n[...]\ndon’t\n[...]\n’s 27 subtypes that are not\n[...]\nI learned Naranjo’s subtypes I had never heard a Self-Preservation Four\n[...]\ndescribed—or a Social Seven or a Social Nine or a Self-Preservation or Sexual Three! These types just don’t exist in most descriptions of the nine types. And, don’t we want to include all the possible types in\n[...]\nway possible?\n[...]\nSelf-Preservation Ones focus on making everything they do more perfect.\n[...]\nare the true\n[...]\nists of the Enne\n[...]\n. They see themselves as highly flawed and try to improve themselves and make every detail of what they do right. These people are the most anxious and worried Ones, but also the most friendly and warm.\n[...]\n—and modeling how to do things right for others. An intellectual\n[...]\n, these Ones have a teacher mentality; they see\n[...]\nrole as helping others see what they already know–how to be perfect\n[...]\nSelf-Preservation Twos seek to gain approval through being charming and youthful. Less oriented to giving and more burdened by helping, they charm others into liking them as an unconscious effort to get people to take care of them. More self-indulgent, playful, and irresponsible than the other two Twos, they are more fearful and ambivalent about connecting with others.\n[...]\nSocial Twos seek to gain approval from others through being powerful, competent, and influential. More a powerful, leader type of person, they take charge of things and play to a larger audience as a way of proving their value.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Instinctual Subtypes\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/subtypes/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUnderneath each Enneagram type runs a different layer of personality — a layer that comes from biology rather than from psychological structure. The three instincts are biologically rooted drives that all humans share but in unequal proportions: the drive toward physical survival and resource security (self-preservation), the drive toward belonging and group navigation (social), and the drive toward intense bonding with specific others (sexual, also called one-to-one or intimate).\n[...]\ninstinct combines with\n[...]\nand three instincts\n[...]\nSelf-preservation (sp). The drive toward physical survival, material security, and bodily well-being. Self-preservation-dominant people pay attention to food, money, shelter, warmth, comfort, health, and routine. They notice whether the room is too cold, whether the budget is balanced, whether there is enough in the pantry. Their attention runs toward the body and its conditions.\n[...]\nSocial (so). The drive toward belonging, status, and navigation of group dynamics. Social-dominant people pay attention to relationships within communities — who is in, who is out, who has power, what the group needs. They notice the political dynamics of a room, the status hierarchy of a workplace, the alliances and exclusions in a friend group. Their attention runs toward the group and its structure.\n[...]\nSexual / one-to-one / intimate (sx). The drive toward intense bonding, attraction, and individual chemistry. Sexual-dominant people pay attention to specific others with disproportionate intensity. They notice charge, magnetism, the felt quality of a particular person's presence. Their attention runs toward the chosen individual rather than the group or the body.\n[...]\nThis lineage matters because the subtype framework is sometimes incorrectly attributed to Riso/Hudson, who introduced their own framework for the instincts in The Wisdom of the Enneagram (1999). Riso and Hudson's instinct framework is distinct from Naranjo's subtype framework, as discussed below.\n[...]\nWisdom of the Enneagram (19\n[...]\n), but their framework is\n[...]\naranjo's.\n[...]\nIn the Riso/Hudson framing, the instincts operate independently of the core type — each instinct has its own characteristic concerns and expressions that show up regardless of which type a person is. A self-preservation-dominant person of any type focuses on resources, comfort, and well-being; a social-dominant person of any type focuses on group dynamics; a sexual-dominant person of any type focuses on intensity and chemistry. The type then modifies how the instinct is expressed.\n[...]\ntypes; the\n[...]\nthe Naranjo"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a88ea885-1950-40b9-b15d-36f548aa1b64","uuid":"7af1ce14-c864-4e08-879f-9fdfb8a43490","timestamp":"2026-06-10T16:54:19.788Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: About the RHETI® - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/rheti/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nAbout the RHETI® - The Enneagram Institute \n\n# The Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator(RHETI® version 2.5)\n\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5) is the world’s most popular Enneagram-based test. It is a scientifically validated, forced-choice personality test with 144 paired statements. The test takes about 40 minutes to complete.\n\nThe RHETI® version 2.5 has been independently scientifically validated. Rather than just indicating your basic type, it produces a full personality profile across all nine types. This provides you with a unique portrait, indicating the relative strengths and weaknesses of the nine types within your overall personality.\n\nThe RHETI® results are available in a PDF format and include your scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for your top three scores. These type descriptions have been revised and updated to provide the most comprehensive type summaries available.\n\n“We both felt the Enneagram as represented by The Enneagram Institute was a more efficacious measure of personality traits than any other, including the DiSC and Myers-Briggs.”\n\n> Mr. Kim and Ms. Janise Pries, El Paso, TexasDirector of Product Integrity and Reliability; Licensed Professional Counselor, Director of Guidance and Counseling\n\nQuestions? Please contact support@enneagraminstitute.com\n\nPURCHASE THE RHETI®\n\n---\n\nTitle: How The Enneagram System Works - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/how-the-enneagram-system-works/\nPublished: 2024-01-11T20:34:04.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe three Instincts (often erroneously\n[...]\n“the subtypes”) are a third set of distinctions that are extremely important for understanding personality. A major aspect of human nature lies in our instinctual “hard wiring” as biological beings. We each are endowed with specific instinctual intelligences that are necessary for our survival as individuals and as a\n[...]\n. We each have a self-preservation instinct (for preserving the body and its life and functioning), a sexual instinct (for extending ourselves in the environment and through the\n[...]\n), and a social instinct (for\n[...]\nThe Enneagram Institute® offers an online test, the Instinctual Variants Questionnaire (IVQ), for helping people determine not only their dominant instinct, but also their Instinctual Stack. The IVQ also provides a detailed personality profile derived from the combination of the test taker’s Enneagram type, wing, and Instinctual Stack.\n[...]\npeople are “nesters”—they seek domestic tranquility and security with a stable, reliable partner\n[...]\nSexual (aka “Attraction”) Instinct\n[...]\n, and tend to be more aggressive, competitive, charged, and emotionally intense than the Self-Pres or\n[...]\ntypes. Sexual\n[...]\nneed to have intense\n[...]\nor else they remain unsatisfied. They enjoy being intensely\n[...]\n—even merged—with\n[...]\n, and can become disenchanted with partners who are unable to meet their need for intense energetic union. Losing yourself in a “fusion” of being is the ideal here, and\n[...]\ntypes are always looking for this state with others and with stimulating objects in their world.\n[...]\nSocial (aka “Adaptive”) Instinct\n[...]\nJust as many people tend to misidentify themselves as Sexual types because they want one-on-one\n[...]\n, many people fail to recognize themselves as\n[...]\ntypes because they get the (false) idea\n[...]\n-Preservation types are interested in adjusting\n[...]\nenvironment to make themselves more\n[...]\nand comfortable,\n[...]\nthe needs of the\n[...]\n. Thus,\n[...]\nand attitudes are\n[...]\npeople and to be\n[...]\ntypes are the most concerned with\n[...]\nthat will have some impact on\n[...]\n, or even broader domains.\n[...]\ntend to be\n[...]\n, more open, engaging, and\n[...]\nresponsible than the other two types. In their primary relationships, they seek partners with whom they can share social activities, wanting their intimates to get involved in projects and events with them. Paradoxically, they actually tend to avoid long periods of exclusive intimacy and quiet solitude, seeing both as potentially limiting. Social types lose their sense of identity and meaning when they are not involved with others in activities that transcend their individual interests.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Get Started with Enneagram Tests - The Enneagram Institute\nURL: https://www.enneagraminstitute.com/get-started-with-enneagram-tests/\nPublished: 2024-02-08T21:48:25.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nRHETI® – Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator\n[...]\n- A comprehensive, personalized PDF report\n- Your scores for all 9 Enneagram Types\n- Expanded Type descriptions for Your Top 3 Types\n- Detailed information on relationship issues, Type compatibility, personality dynamics, and the Levels of Development\n- Personal growth recommendations\n- No surprise monthly billing. One-time fee includes the test and detailed report.\n[...]\nThe IVQ is the first online test to measure our three basic instinctual intelligences: Self-preservation, Social, and Sexual. Find out which is dominant for you.\n[...]\n- A comprehensive, personalized PDF report\n- Your scores for all three Instincts: Self-preservation, Social, Sexual\n- In-depth information about the Instincts\n- Bonus content about the Instinctual Variants for your specific Enneagram Type\n- Personal growth recommendations\n[...]\nKnowing our Enneagram Type assists us with inner observation, self-knowledge, and personal growth. With our official, scientifically-validated Enneagram test, the Riso Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI®), you will receive a comprehensive, personalized Enneagram profile report with scores for all 9 Types, expanded Type descriptions for your top three Types, and much more.\n[...]\n### Our RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram Types\n[...]\nOur RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram\n[...]\nUse the RHETI (Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator) Enneagram Test and the IVQ (Instinctual Variant Questionnaire) with employees, clients, groups, and individuals to help them discover their Enneagram Type and learn about their Instincts. Volume discounts apply.\n[...]\n### Our RHETI® test provides an in-depth analysis of your top 3 Enneagram\n[...]\n- Includes detailed\n[...]\nRHETI® results are emailed to you in PDF format and include a test taker’s scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for the top three scores. IVQ results come in PDF format and include a test taker’s scores for all three Instincts, as well as general descriptions of the Instinctual Variants. Though knowledge of one’s primary Enneagram type is not necessary and does not affect the IVQ score, those who choose to enter their primary Enneagram type receive brief bonus content specific to their type.\n[...]\nOnce you have your RHETI® results, dive deeper by taking our Instinctual Variant Questionnaire, IVQ test. The Instinctual Variant Questionnaire (IVQ v2.0) will help you understand the role that all three Instincts play in your life. Once you have discovered your Instinctual Stack, you can understand your Enneagram type with even more depth and clarity.\n\n---\n\nTitle: RHETI Test | Russ Hudson\nURL: https://russhudson.com/rheti-test/\nPublished: 2020-06-02T16:35:03.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nRHETI Test | Russ Hudson\n\n## RHETI Test\n\n# Russ Hudson\n\n## The Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5)\n\nThe Riso-Hudson Enneagram Type Indicator (RHETI® version 2.5) is the world’s most popular Enneagram-based test. It is a scientifically validated, forced-choice personality test with 144 paired statements. The test takes about 40 minutes to complete.\n\nThe RHETI® version 2.5 has been independently scientifically validated. Rather than just indicating your basic type, however, the RHETI® produces a full personality profile across all nine types. This provides you with a unique portrait, indicating the relative strengths and weaknesses of the nine types within your overall personality.\n\nThe RHETI® results are available in a PDF format and include your scores for all nine types in a full-spectrum profile, as well as the Expanded Type Descriptions (of over 2,500 words each) for your top three scores. These type descriptions have been revised and updated to provide the most comprehensive type summaries available.\n\n## Enjoy Russ' Free Monthly Presence Practice and other news.\n\n## Success! You have been added to our mailing list. Check your inbox or spam for your confirmation. Please mark the email as NOT SPAM and move to your inbox.\n\nFirst Name\n\nLast Name\n\nEmail\n\nSubscribe Now\n\nBy providing your email, you agree to receive our marketing materials, and we do not share your information with 3rd parties.\n\nRuss Hudson is a gifted teacher and wise scholar who offers some of the deepest and most comprehensive understanding of the transformative power of the enneagram. By helping me to become aware of the habitual patterns of thinking and acting that keep me a prisoner of my personality, his work has allowed me to live a more soul-directed life. The enneagram is complex and multi-dimensional, and I always look forward to hearing more from Russ about the unfolding nature of his beautiful work.\n\nCheryl Richardson\n\nAuthor of, Waking Up in Winter: In Search of What Really Matters at Midlife\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Instinctual Subtype Dimension of the Enneagram — Beatrice Chestnut\nURL: https://www.beatricechestnut.com/posts/instinctual-subtypes\nPublished: 2019-05-28T15:12:55.000Z\nAuthor: Written By  Amanda Braga\nHighlights:\nthe three “instincts” refer to our biological survival drives—those of 1.) Self-Preservation, 2.) Relating to others generally and in Social groups, and 3.) Sexual relationships, or One-to-One bonding, and other types of fusion experiences.\n[...]\nThe subtypes are the 27 personalities –more specific, more nuanced versions of the main type, with distinct traits and patterns–that you get when you multiply 3 x 9. Rather than being just “added” together — as in Type X + Instinct A = Type X who does Instinct A behaviors, the mixture of the main Type passion and patterns with a specific dominant instinct (and even mores an “instinct sequence” — which is first, second, and repressed — is more alchemical. The work of Claudio Naranjo in discerning and articulating these very accurate and revealing subtype descriptions, in my view, cannot be overstated.\n[...]\nto break into\n[...]\nby subtype, I saw that they had written on my piece of paper, “\n[...]\nTwo. I\n[...]\nthat the day\n[...]\n-Preservation\n[...]\n. I didn’t like that. I\n[...]\nthat’s not me…I’\n[...]\ndon’t\n[...]\n’s 27 subtypes that are not\n[...]\nI learned Naranjo’s subtypes I had never heard a Self-Preservation Four\n[...]\ndescribed—or a Social Seven or a Social Nine or a Self-Preservation or Sexual Three! These types just don’t exist in most descriptions of the nine types. And, don’t we want to include all the possible types in\n[...]\nway possible?\n[...]\nSelf-Preservation Ones focus on making everything they do more perfect.\n[...]\nare the true\n[...]\nists of the Enne\n[...]\n. They see themselves as highly flawed and try to improve themselves and make every detail of what they do right. These people are the most anxious and worried Ones, but also the most friendly and warm.\n[...]\n—and modeling how to do things right for others. An intellectual\n[...]\n, these Ones have a teacher mentality; they see\n[...]\nrole as helping others see what they already know–how to be perfect\n[...]\nSelf-Preservation Twos seek to gain approval through being charming and youthful. Less oriented to giving and more burdened by helping, they charm others into liking them as an unconscious effort to get people to take care of them. More self-indulgent, playful, and irresponsible than the other two Twos, they are more fearful and ambivalent about connecting with others.\n[...]\nSocial Twos seek to gain approval from others through being powerful, competent, and influential. More a powerful, leader type of person, they take charge of things and play to a larger audience as a way of proving their value.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Instinctual Subtypes\nURL: https://sociotype.com/enneagram/subtypes/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUnderneath each Enneagram type runs a different layer of personality — a layer that comes from biology rather than from psychological structure. The three instincts are biologically rooted drives that all humans share but in unequal proportions: the drive toward physical survival and resource security (self-preservation), the drive toward belonging and group navigation (social), and the drive toward intense bonding with specific others (sexual, also called one-to-one or intimate).\n[...]\ninstinct combines with\n[...]\nand three instincts\n[...]\nSelf-preservation (sp). The drive toward physical survival, material security, and bodily well-being. Self-preservation-dominant people pay attention to food, money, shelter, warmth, comfort, health, and routine. They notice whether the room is too cold, whether the budget is balanced, whether there is enough in the pantry. Their attention runs toward the body and its conditions.\n[...]\nSocial (so). The drive toward belonging, status, and navigation of group dynamics. Social-dominant people pay attention to relationships within communities — who is in, who is out, who has power, what the group needs. They notice the political dynamics of a room, the status hierarchy of a workplace, the alliances and exclusions in a friend group. Their attention runs toward the group and its structure.\n[...]\nSexual / one-to-one / intimate (sx). The drive toward intense bonding, attraction, and individual chemistry. Sexual-dominant people pay attention to specific others with disproportionate intensity. They notice charge, magnetism, the felt quality of a particular person's presence. Their attention runs toward the chosen individual rather than the group or the body.\n[...]\nThis lineage matters because the subtype framework is sometimes incorrectly attributed to Riso/Hudson, who introduced their own framework for the instincts in The Wisdom of the Enneagram (1999). Riso and Hudson's instinct framework is distinct from Naranjo's subtype framework, as discussed below.\n[...]\nWisdom of the Enneagram (19\n[...]\n), but their framework is\n[...]\naranjo's.\n[...]\nIn the Riso/Hudson framing, the instincts operate independently of the core type — each instinct has its own characteristic concerns and expressions that show up regardless of which type a person is. A self-preservation-dominant person of any type focuses on resources, comfort, and well-being; a social-dominant person of any type focuses on group dynamics; a sexual-dominant person of any type focuses on intensity and chemistry. The type then modifies how the instinct is expressed.\n[...]\ntypes; the\n[...]\nthe Naranjo","_meta":{"searchTime":1043}}]}
