proficiency.\n[...]\nTeam coaching with our Enneagram-certified coaches starts at $3,500 for a two-hour virtual development session with up to 10 participant for a limited time. This includes:\n[...]\n#### A 2-hour remote-based experience with a certified Enneagram coach.\n[...]\n#### Reports to understand your team’s Enneagram style with our Team Enneagram results reporting.\n[...]\n#### Learning the team’s needs and\n[...]\nteaming outcomes via a 6\n[...]\n-minute Client Intake Session.\n[...]\n#### Understanding of each team member’s personality tendencies with Enneagram assessments and confidential results reporting.\n[...]\nBy utilizing the Enneagram, leaders gain valuable insights into what motivates, challenges, and drives productivity for each individual on their team. This awareness allows for tailored approaches to communication, task delegation, and overall team management.\n[...]\n#### Our Enneagram Program is your powerful path to better teaming and higher success. With our Certified Coaches, Tailored Coaching Approach, and Proven Measurable Results, you can propel your organization to new heights.\n[...]\n#### In the realm of organizational success, cohesive teams are pivotal. Teams that collaborate seamlessly, trust each other, communicate effectively, and navigate complex issues together are essential for reaching the organization's goals. The Enneagram serves as a transformative tool, providing a profound understanding of individual and team dynamics. This insight, when integrated into team coaching with Level Up EQ, facilitates the development of success-oriented teams. These teams, in turn, drive enhanced productivity and success, becoming the backbone of organizational growth and achievement.\n[...]\n#### Throughout the facilitated program, Level Up EQ coaches incorporate emotional intelligence training, accountability strategies, and feedback sessions that allow for trackable, measurable improvement and change. Ready to take the next step? Reach out to us for a complimentary 30-minute consultation. Let's chat about where you currently stand, where you aspire to be, and how Level Up EQ, combined with the power of the Enneagram, can be your ideal partner on this transformative journey.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram Coaching for Senior Leaders and Teams\nURL: https://workinvigorated.com/enneagram-coaching/\nPublished: 2025-08-02T16:03:47.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Enneagram is a cornerstone of our coaching philosophy for business and secondary education leaders. We believe that skilled Enneagram coaching is the most powerful catalyst for individuals seeking profound professional and personal growth, and for organizations committed to building high-performing, engaged, cohesive teams.\n[...]\nAs a certified Enneagram coach with a background in business consulting, Kimberly brings more than insight – she brings precision. She uses the Enneagram not just as a self-awareness tool, but as a strategic lens to uncover patterns that shape how leaders think, communicate and lead. Her work helps individuals and teams break through plateaus, navigate conflict, and lead with greater clarity, courage and impact.\n[...]\nShe is an experienced Enneagram assessment and coaching professional, certified as an iEQ9 Integrative Enneagram Practitioner, Levels 1 and 2.\n[...]\nLevel 1 certification focuses on a deep understanding of the Enneagram for individual growth, equipping certified coaches to expertly interpret the iEQ9 professional reports and provide powerful one-on-one coaching. Coaches learn to debrief clients on their core type, subtypes and turn insights into a unique development path to unlock profound growth.\n[...]\nBuilding on Level 1, the Level 2 certification centers on TEAM and group dynamics, training Level 2 coaches to interpret iEQ9 Team Reports and facilitate workshops. Those certified at this level have developed the skills to apply the Enneagram in complex organizational settings, improving team cohesion, communication and overall performance.\n[...]\nTeams that work well together outperform those who don’t. For work groups, the benefits of working with the Enneagram as a cohort include:\n[...]\n- Understanding what motivates each team member and collective dynamics of your team\n- Improving each team member’s ability to work with others\n- Making individual differences a team strength\n- Having more empathy for fellow team members\n- Learning how to build a happier, healthier, high-performing team\n[...]\nYes! Our team Enneagram coaching and Enneagram workshops are popular and powerful! Reach out for details and to book a workshop program for your employees or leadership cohort.\n[...]\n“I had the privilege of working with Kimberly Harris through a\n[...]\ncoaching program, and the experience was insightful, impactful, and truly\n[...]\nboth personally and professionally. Kimberly is approachable\n[...]\nand a 36\n[...]\nassessment, she helped me better understand my\n[...]\nand purpose. I would strongly recommend Kimberly as a coach to leaders who are\n[...]\nto taking their leadership to the next level with greater self-awareness","_meta":{"searchTime":1029.7}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_qebb1ijek9p3_3","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Distinctives of the Narrative Tradition - The Narrative Enneagram\nURL: https://www.narrativeenneagram.org/distinctives-of-the-narrative-tradition/\nPublished: 2024-04-03T19:54:29.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nDistinctives of the Narrative Tradition - The Narrative Enneagram\n\n### What makes The Narrative Enneagram unique among Enneagram schools and training programs?\n\nPeople often ask what is distinctive about The Narrative Enneagram and how we teach the Enneagram system.\n\nIn addition to our 35-year history and the honor of being named the first ever International Enneagram Association’s Accredited School with Distinction, there are 7 distinctives that provide the foundation for everything we do.\n\n#### Distinctives of the Narrative Tradition\n\n##### Centering Experience\n\nIn addition to teaching historical and innovative Enneagram theory, we center people’s lived experiences as authoritative, particularly expressed through the use of panels and typing interviews.\n\n##### Self-Discovery\n\nWe teach that Enneagram type is determined by motivation rather than behavior and that knowing our type is inner work so that each person is responsible for determining their own type; we do not type others.\n\n##### Honoring Diverse Perspectives\n\nWith a deep commitment to diversity, equity, inclusion, and belonging, we challenge learners to recognize the impact of cultural and social contexts in which the Enneagram is taught and described, in order to make this system more expansive and accessible for all people.\n\n##### Appreciation of Types\n\nWe appreciate and value the necessity of all nine type structures, which offer gifts as well as challenges, and so we meet each person where they are with compassion.\n\n##### Group Transformation\n\nWe recognize that transformation comes through the group working together in a generous, compassionate field between and among participants so that all participants can share their experiences and deepen their understanding.\n\n##### Three-Centered Learning\n\nWe engage all three centers in learning – head, heart, and body – bringing concepts and ideas into the inner experience through self-awareness, kindness to self, and somatic practice.\n\n##### Path to Growth\n\nWe engage the three perspectives of psychology, spirituality, and somatics as the path to growth and the full integration of learning.\n\n###### Join us at an upcoming program to experience these distinctives in action. We’d love to see you soon!\n\nrem()\n\n#### Sign Up for Our Newsletter\n\nGet monthly Enneagram insights, updates, and stories\n\n---\n\nTitle: Appologies to Helen Palmer – Psychology And You\nURL: https://psychologyandyou.ca/appologies-to-helen-palmer/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nI’m going to mess up the dates here, but between around the 1980’s to the 2010’s, there were two mainstream Enneagram schools in the United States (and the world)- there was the East Coast school in New York with Don Riso and Russ Hudson, and then the West coast school in California with Helen Palmer and Dr. David Daniels at Stanford. I believe the California school came first by several years, but I don’t know how many.\n[...]\nFrom what I understand, there was rancor and/or competition between the two schools where each pair of teachers was trying to fill in the type descriptions as clearly and authoritatively as possible and make their mark on this new, wide open field of study. I think it was kind of the wild west back then, and there was a competition to see who would come out on top- I don’t remember where I read this, but I’m pretty sure I heard this somewhere- sorry for the vagueness, but this just speaks to how little I had to base my dismissiveness on. I also think I remember someone criticizing her use of the term “Narrative Tradition”- as if the Enneagram has been passed down orally throughout history (it kind of has, but also not really). Or there was some criticism about her use of panels (putting people up on stage before they fully understood their type).\n[...]\nAnyway, I had already aligned myself with the New York school after having attended their first two training programs in the mid-2010’s, and loved how systematically they organized each type. I had read Helen Palmer’s seminal The Enneagram in Love and Work: Understanding your Intimate and Business Relationships and it was more prosaic, and while I got a lot out of it, I liked Riso and Hudson’s more organized way of breaking down the types.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Comparison of Two Authors’ Views of the Seven by a Type Seven - Enneagram Monthly\nURL: https://enneagrammonthly.com/comparison-of-two-authors-views-of-the-seven-by-a-type-seven/\nPublished: 2026-04-10T00:57:54.000Z\nAuthor: Jack Labanauskas\nHighlights:\nComparison of Two Authors’ Views of the Seven by a Type Seven - Enneagram Monthly\n\nMona Coates, Ph.D. In an attempt to understand my own SEVEN-ness more completely, I conducted the following search for deeper explanations by comparing and contrasting the works of Don Richard Riso, Personality Types (1987) and Understanding The Enneagram (1990) with the works of Helen Palmer, The Enneagram: Understanding Yourself and the Others in Your Life (1988) and The Enneagram in Love and Work (1995). These books will be referenced in shorthand as: Riso’s Personality Types and Understandi...\n\nSubscribe today (returning users login) to access more of this article as well as the entire Enneagram Monthly archive.\n\nUsername\n\nPassword\n\nRemember Me\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram’s Narrative Tradition | David N. Daniels, M.D. Enneagram Expert\nURL: https://drdaviddaniels.com/the-narrative-tradition/\nPublished: 2024-08-22T22:26:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n#### SYNOPSIS OF ARTICLE: What we’ve come to call the “Narrative Tradition” is a method of both learning and teaching that is based on each of the nine personality type speaking for themselves. It’s a philosophy wherein we individually contribute our own self-knowledge and personal path to becoming integrated beings. The Narrative Tradition relies on in-depth panels of exemplars, interviews, and small group processes.\n[...]\nHelen Palmer along with others in Berkeley, California began conducting panel interviewing of the nine Enneagram personality types in the 1970s. This method, coined “the Narrative Tradition,” quickly became a powerful and effective teaching method. It’s one thing to read theory and concepts presented in a book. It’s another to witness a personality type speak for itself. She and I [1] have been teaching the Enneagram using the Narrative Tradition method in our Enneagram Professional Training Program (EPTP) since 1988, the year we established the first Enneagram training program. Our goal was to put standards in place for this work. In this way, panels of speakers of the types reveal their inner worlds and realities publicly. Each individual participant teaches the rest of us in a manner that no didactic method ever could. Our organization, THE NARRATIVE ENNEAGRAM (TNE), is now in several countries worldwide and has been growing year by year. Many people and teachers know it as the Palmer-Daniels Enneagram Training Program.\n[...]\nThe Narrative Tradition’s inquiry method\n[...]\npanels, small group\n[...]\ninterviewing elucidates each type’s struggles,\n[...]\n, strengths, basic structure, and paths of development. The grass roots philosophy of self-discovery and self-expression fundamental to the ultimate goal of self-development is embedded in this approach. The types continuously teach us about themselves at ever deepening levels of awareness, and we learn from exploring with them. The panel method recognizes that type is based on the internal structure of reality, which implicitly is largely non-cognitive and outside of awareness until we “wake up,” thanks to the development of self-observation and inquiry. In addition, this method in no way demeans either the written word or explicit cognitive learning, both of which heighten clarity, facilitate discussion, and are readily disseminated. Thus, the Enneagram ultimately is an “inside job” of coming to know your own attentional style and basic motivation behind perceptions and behaviors. The system is not primarily about external behavior, but rather about how\n[...]\nrelates to attentional style, motivation, and spiritual experience. In our view, there is no better way to\n[...]\nthan through the Narrative Tradition’s\n\n---\n\nTitle: The many faces of the Enneagram\nURL: https://chloeeved.substack.com/p/the-many-faces-of-the-enneagram\nPublished: 2025-11-17T12:43:23.000Z\nAuthor: Psychology and/ or birds 🐦\nHighlights:\nIt was not until the 1950s that South American Oscar Ichazo developed the Enneagram symbol into a pyscho-spiritual system. He founded the ‘Arica’ school where he taught a group of students the basics of Enneagram theory. He created a system of 108 Enneagrams – which included the Enneagram of the passions, the Enneagram of fixations, the Enneagram of the virtues, and the Enneagram of holy ideas. Ichazo saw the Enneagram as a way of examining the structure of the soul, and the ways in which ego can distort authenticity.\n[...]\nClaudio Naranjo, a student of Icazo’s, developed the original Enneagram of personality in the 1970s. He fleshed out the personality structures of the 9 Enneagram types, building on Ichazo’s fixations and passions. He also developed the ‘27 subtypes’, exploring how each of the 9 Enneagram types present differently depending on whether the ‘self-preservation’, ‘social’ or ‘sexual’ survival instinct is dominant.\n[...]\nThe Enneagram personality types we know today evolved from Naranjo’s and Ichazo’s ideas. Naranjo initially designed the Enneagram to be used in psychological practice, linking most of the 27 types with recognised psychological conditions or neuroses. It was his students, Riso and Hudson, who created the version of the Enneagram we see popularized today. Naranjo only published his Enneagram model later in an attempt to correct misinformation. Nonetheless, most Enneagram content online, including Youtubers, uses Riso and Hudson’s version. In some cases, they simplify Riso and Hudson’s version and dilute the original theories even more.\n[...]\nI think it’s fair to say that Naranjo was mostly interested in explaining\n[...]\ncore fixations and passions of\n[...]\n, and how this led to\n[...]\nHis descriptions of the\n[...]\nillustrate how the passion of\n[...]\nWhile this means his type portrayals tend to be more negative (though not always\n[...]\n‘worst case scenario’\n[...]\nunderstand why this\n[...]\nand Hudson made\n[...]\nthing that makes their version more\n[...]\nexpert Beatrice Chesnut has also created\n[...]\nlevels of development\n[...]\nher interpretation of\n[...]\n. In my opinion\n[...]\n. In fact once you understand\n[...]\n, the general descriptions of healthy and\n[...]\n. We’ll see more how different subtypes face different challenges later on\n[...]\npart of N\n[...]\nto take on"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a88ea885-1950-40b9-b15d-36f548aa1b64","uuid":"7fd3d684-2cc7-4fea-8f18-415821188b22","timestamp":"2026-06-10T16:54:32.813Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Distinctives of the Narrative Tradition - The Narrative Enneagram\nURL: https://www.narrativeenneagram.org/distinctives-of-the-narrative-tradition/\nPublished: 2024-04-03T19:54:29.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nDistinctives of the Narrative Tradition - The Narrative Enneagram\n\n### What makes The Narrative Enneagram unique among Enneagram schools and training programs?\n\nPeople often ask what is distinctive about The Narrative Enneagram and how we teach the Enneagram system.\n\nIn addition to our 35-year history and the honor of being named the first ever International Enneagram Association’s Accredited School with Distinction, there are 7 distinctives that provide the foundation for everything we do.\n\n#### Distinctives of the Narrative Tradition\n\n##### Centering Experience\n\nIn addition to teaching historical and innovative Enneagram theory, we center people’s lived experiences as authoritative, particularly expressed through the use of panels and typing interviews.\n\n##### Self-Discovery\n\nWe teach that Enneagram type is determined by motivation rather than behavior and that knowing our type is inner work so that each person is responsible for determining their own type; we do not type others.\n\n##### Honoring Diverse Perspectives\n\nWith a deep commitment to diversity, equity, inclusion, and belonging, we challenge learners to recognize the impact of cultural and social contexts in which the Enneagram is taught and described, in order to make this system more expansive and accessible for all people.\n\n##### Appreciation of Types\n\nWe appreciate and value the necessity of all nine type structures, which offer gifts as well as challenges, and so we meet each person where they are with compassion.\n\n##### Group Transformation\n\nWe recognize that transformation comes through the group working together in a generous, compassionate field between and among participants so that all participants can share their experiences and deepen their understanding.\n\n##### Three-Centered Learning\n\nWe engage all three centers in learning – head, heart, and body – bringing concepts and ideas into the inner experience through self-awareness, kindness to self, and somatic practice.\n\n##### Path to Growth\n\nWe engage the three perspectives of psychology, spirituality, and somatics as the path to growth and the full integration of learning.\n\n###### Join us at an upcoming program to experience these distinctives in action. We’d love to see you soon!\n\nrem()\n\n#### Sign Up for Our Newsletter\n\nGet monthly Enneagram insights, updates, and stories\n\n---\n\nTitle: Appologies to Helen Palmer – Psychology And You\nURL: https://psychologyandyou.ca/appologies-to-helen-palmer/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nI’m going to mess up the dates here, but between around the 1980’s to the 2010’s, there were two mainstream Enneagram schools in the United States (and the world)- there was the East Coast school in New York with Don Riso and Russ Hudson, and then the West coast school in California with Helen Palmer and Dr. David Daniels at Stanford. I believe the California school came first by several years, but I don’t know how many.\n[...]\nFrom what I understand, there was rancor and/or competition between the two schools where each pair of teachers was trying to fill in the type descriptions as clearly and authoritatively as possible and make their mark on this new, wide open field of study. I think it was kind of the wild west back then, and there was a competition to see who would come out on top- I don’t remember where I read this, but I’m pretty sure I heard this somewhere- sorry for the vagueness, but this just speaks to how little I had to base my dismissiveness on. I also think I remember someone criticizing her use of the term “Narrative Tradition”- as if the Enneagram has been passed down orally throughout history (it kind of has, but also not really). Or there was some criticism about her use of panels (putting people up on stage before they fully understood their type).\n[...]\nAnyway, I had already aligned myself with the New York school after having attended their first two training programs in the mid-2010’s, and loved how systematically they organized each type. I had read Helen Palmer’s seminal The Enneagram in Love and Work: Understanding your Intimate and Business Relationships and it was more prosaic, and while I got a lot out of it, I liked Riso and Hudson’s more organized way of breaking down the types.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Comparison of Two Authors’ Views of the Seven by a Type Seven - Enneagram Monthly\nURL: https://enneagrammonthly.com/comparison-of-two-authors-views-of-the-seven-by-a-type-seven/\nPublished: 2026-04-10T00:57:54.000Z\nAuthor: Jack Labanauskas\nHighlights:\nComparison of Two Authors’ Views of the Seven by a Type Seven - Enneagram Monthly\n\nMona Coates, Ph.D. In an attempt to understand my own SEVEN-ness more completely, I conducted the following search for deeper explanations by comparing and contrasting the works of Don Richard Riso, Personality Types (1987) and Understanding The Enneagram (1990) with the works of Helen Palmer, The Enneagram: Understanding Yourself and the Others in Your Life (1988) and The Enneagram in Love and Work (1995). These books will be referenced in shorthand as: Riso’s Personality Types and Understandi...\n\nSubscribe today (returning users login) to access more of this article as well as the entire Enneagram Monthly archive.\n\nUsername\n\nPassword\n\nRemember Me\n\n---\n\nTitle: Enneagram’s Narrative Tradition | David N. Daniels, M.D. Enneagram Expert\nURL: https://drdaviddaniels.com/the-narrative-tradition/\nPublished: 2024-08-22T22:26:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n#### SYNOPSIS OF ARTICLE: What we’ve come to call the “Narrative Tradition” is a method of both learning and teaching that is based on each of the nine personality type speaking for themselves. It’s a philosophy wherein we individually contribute our own self-knowledge and personal path to becoming integrated beings. The Narrative Tradition relies on in-depth panels of exemplars, interviews, and small group processes.\n[...]\nHelen Palmer along with others in Berkeley, California began conducting panel interviewing of the nine Enneagram personality types in the 1970s. This method, coined “the Narrative Tradition,” quickly became a powerful and effective teaching method. It’s one thing to read theory and concepts presented in a book. It’s another to witness a personality type speak for itself. She and I [1] h